{"title_page": "Da 5 Bloods", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Da 5 Bloods\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Spike Lee]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Jon Kilik\n*Spike Lee\n*Beatriz Levin\n*[[Lloyd Levin]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Danny Bilson]]\n*[[Paul De Meo]]\n*Spike Lee\n*[[Kevin Willmott]]\n}}\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Chadwick Boseman]]\n*[[Paul Walter Hauser]]\n*[[Norm Lewis]] \n*[[Delroy Lindo]]\n*[[Jonathan Majors]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Terence Blanchard]]\n| cinematography = [[Newton Thomas Sigel]]\n| editing        = Adam Gough\n| studio         = [[40 Acres and a Mule Filmworks]]\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = \n| runtime        = 154 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Da 5 Bloods''''' is an upcoming [[epic films|epic]] [[war drama]] film directed by [[Spike Lee]]. It stars [[Chadwick Boseman]], [[Paul Walter Hauser]], [[Norm Lewis]], [[Delroy Lindo]] and [[Jonathan Majors]].\n\n==Premise==\nFour African American [[Vietnam veterans]] return to Vietnam. They are in search of the remains of their fallen squad leader and the promise of buried treasure. These heroes battle forces of humanity and nature while confronted by the lasting ravages of the immorality of the Vietnam War.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Chadwick Boseman]]\n*[[Paul Walter Hauser]] as Simon\n*[[Norm Lewis]]\n*[[Delroy Lindo]]\n*[[Jonathan Majors]] as David\n*[[Clarke Peters]]\n*[[Isiah Whitlock Jr.]] \n*[[Jean Reno]]\n*[[M\u00e9lanie Thierry]]\n*[[Jasper P\u00e4\u00e4kk\u00f6nen]] as Larry Thorne\n*[[Veronica Ngo]] as [[Hanoi Hannah]]\n*[[Giancarlo Esposito]]\n\n==Production==\nIn January 2019, it was reported that [[Spike Lee]] would direct ''Da 5 Bloods'', a film written by [[Danny Bilson]] and [[Paul De Meo]] with adaptions by Lee and Kevin Wilmott. [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Giancarlo Esposito]], and [[Don Cheadle]] were being eyed for lead roles in the film. Filming began on March 23, 2019, with [[Vietnam]] and [[Thailand]] ([[South East Asia]]) as filming locations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/02/spike-lee-chadwick-boseman-da-5-bloods.html |title=Chadwick Boseman to Star in Spike Lee's New Movie, Vietnam Veteran Drama Da 5 Bloods |first=Scott |last=Russell |date=13 February 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |magazine=[[Paste Magazine]]}}</ref> It was announced in February 2019 that [[Netflix]] would distribute the film, with [[Chadwick Boseman]], [[Delroy Lindo]], and [[Jean Reno]] set to co-star in the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/chadwick-boseman-spike-lee-da-5-bloods-movie-netflix-1202556104/ |title=Chadwick Boseman Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 At Netflix |first=Patrick |last=Hipes |date=12 February 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> [[Jonathan Majors]] entered negotiations to join later that month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/spike-lee-netflix-movie-da-5-bloods-adds-jonathan-majors-1202560490/ |title=Jonathan Majors In Talks For Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 At Netflix |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=19 February 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> In March 2019, [[Paul Walter Hauser]], [[Clarke Peters]], [[Isiah Whitlock Jr.]], [[Norm Lewis]], [[M\u00e9lanie Thierry]], and [[Jasper P\u00e4\u00e4kk\u00f6nen]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/paul-walter-hauser-spike-lee-for-da-5-bloods-netflix-blackkklansman-1202570022/ |title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Actor Paul Walter Hauser To Reunite With Spike Lee For \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Dino |last=Day-Ramos |date=March 5, 2019 |access-date=March 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/netflix-spike-lee-chadwick-boseman-da-5-bloods-adds-clarke-peters-isiah-whitlockjr-melanie-thierry-1202574535/ |title=Spike Lee & Netflix\u2019s Vietnam Pic \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 Adds Cast Including Clarke Peters, Isiah Whitlock Jr & M\u00e9lanie Thierry |first=Andreas |last=Wiseman |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> Esposito was also confirmed for the cast.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://screenrant.com/spike-lee-da-5-bloods-cast-paul-walter-hauser/ |title=BlacKkKlansman Actor Reuniting With Spike Lee For Da 5 Bloods |first=Chris |last=Agar |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |work=[[Screen Rant]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|9777644}}\n\n{{Spike Lee}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Spike Lee]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films set in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films about veterans]]\n[[Category:Upcoming Netflix original films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Da 5 Bloods\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Spike Lee]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Jon Kilik\n*Spike Lee\n*Beatriz Levin\n*[[Lloyd Levin]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Danny Bilson]]\n*[[Paul De Meo]]\n*Spike Lee\n*[[Kevin Willmott]]\n}}\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Chadwick Boseman]]\n*[[Paul Walter Hauser]]\n*[[Norm Lewis]] \n*[[Delroy Lindo]]\n*[[Jonathan Majors]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Terence Blanchard]]\n| cinematography = [[Newton Thomas Sigel]]\n| editing        = Adam Gough\n| studio         = [[40 Acres and a Mule Filmworks]]\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = \n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Da 5 Bloods''''' is an upcoming [[epic films|epic]] [[war drama]] film directed by [[Spike Lee]]. It stars [[Chadwick Boseman]], [[Paul Walter Hauser]], [[Norm Lewis]], [[Delroy Lindo]] and [[Jonathan Majors]].\n\n==Premise==\nFour African American [[Vietnam veterans]] return to Vietnam. They are in search of the remains of their fallen squad leader and the promise of buried treasure. These heroes battle forces of humanity and nature while confronted by the lasting ravages of the immorality of the Vietnam War.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Chadwick Boseman]]\n*[[Paul Walter Hauser]] as Simon\n*[[Norm Lewis]]\n*[[Delroy Lindo]]\n*[[Jonathan Majors]] as David\n*[[Clarke Peters]]\n*[[Isiah Whitlock Jr.]] \n*[[Jean Reno]]\n*[[M\u00e9lanie Thierry]]\n*[[Jasper P\u00e4\u00e4kk\u00f6nen]] as Larry Thorne\n*[[Veronica Ngo]] as [[Hanoi Hannah]]\n*[[Giancarlo Esposito]]\n\n==Production==\nIn January 2019, it was reported that [[Spike Lee]] would direct ''Da 5 Bloods'', a film written by [[Danny Bilson]] and [[Paul De Meo]] with adaptions by Lee and Kevin Wilmott. [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Giancarlo Esposito]], and [[Don Cheadle]] were being eyed for lead roles in the film. Filming began on March 23, 2019, with [[Vietnam]] and [[Thailand]] ([[South East Asia]]) as filming locations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/02/spike-lee-chadwick-boseman-da-5-bloods.html |title=Chadwick Boseman to Star in Spike Lee's New Movie, Vietnam Veteran Drama Da 5 Bloods |first=Scott |last=Russell |date=13 February 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |magazine=[[Paste Magazine]]}}</ref> It was announced in February 2019 that [[Netflix]] would distribute the film, with [[Chadwick Boseman]], [[Delroy Lindo]], and [[Jean Reno]] set to co-star in the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/chadwick-boseman-spike-lee-da-5-bloods-movie-netflix-1202556104/ |title=Chadwick Boseman Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 At Netflix |first=Patrick |last=Hipes |date=12 February 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> [[Jonathan Majors]] entered negotiations to join later that month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/spike-lee-netflix-movie-da-5-bloods-adds-jonathan-majors-1202560490/ |title=Jonathan Majors In Talks For Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 At Netflix |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=19 February 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> In March 2019, [[Paul Walter Hauser]], [[Clarke Peters]], [[Isiah Whitlock Jr.]], [[Norm Lewis]], [[M\u00e9lanie Thierry]], and [[Jasper P\u00e4\u00e4kk\u00f6nen]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/paul-walter-hauser-spike-lee-for-da-5-bloods-netflix-blackkklansman-1202570022/ |title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Actor Paul Walter Hauser To Reunite With Spike Lee For \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Dino |last=Day-Ramos |date=March 5, 2019 |access-date=March 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/netflix-spike-lee-chadwick-boseman-da-5-bloods-adds-clarke-peters-isiah-whitlockjr-melanie-thierry-1202574535/ |title=Spike Lee & Netflix\u2019s Vietnam Pic \u2018Da 5 Bloods\u2019 Adds Cast Including Clarke Peters, Isiah Whitlock Jr & M\u00e9lanie Thierry |first=Andreas |last=Wiseman |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> Esposito was also confirmed for the cast.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://screenrant.com/spike-lee-da-5-bloods-cast-paul-walter-hauser/ |title=BlacKkKlansman Actor Reuniting With Spike Lee For Da 5 Bloods |first=Chris |last=Agar |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |work=[[Screen Rant]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|9777644}}\n\n{{Spike Lee}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Spike Lee]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films set in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films about veterans]]\n[[Category:Upcoming Netflix original films]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:1100:c5e0:68b8:1f7e:da6b:db88", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Da_5_Bloods"}
{"title_page": "Latin America and the Caribbean", "text_new": "The term '''Latin America and the Caribbean''' ('''LAC''')<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/new/en/unesco/worldwide/latin-america-and-the-caribbean/ Latin America and the Caribbean]</ref> is an [[English language|English-language]] [[acronym]] referring to the [[Caribbean]] and [[Latin America]] region. The term LAC covers an extensive region, extending from [[Bahamas]] and [[Mexico]] to [[Argentina]] and [[Chile]]. The region consists over 670,230,000 people {{as of|2016|lc=y}}, and spanned for {{convert|21,951,000|km2|sqmi}}.\n\n== List of countries and territories by subregion ==\n=== Central America ===\n{{Main|Central America}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=85%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Belize}}\n* {{flag|Costa Rica}}\n* {{flag|El Salvador}}\n* {{flag|Guatemala}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Honduras}}\n* {{flag|Mexico}}<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Nicaragua}}\n* {{flag|Panama}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> The [[United Nations geoscheme|UN]] includes [[Mexico]] in [[Central America]]<ref>[https://unstats.un.org/unsd/methodology/m49/ UNSD Methodology \u2013 Standard country or area codes for statistical use (M49)]</ref>.\n\n=== South America ===\n{{Main|South America}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Argentina}}\n* {{flag|Bolivia}}\n* {{flag|Bouvet Island}} ([[Norway]])\n* {{flag|Brazil}}\n* {{flag|Chile}}\n* {{flag|Colombia}}\n* {{flag|Ecuador}} (including the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]])\n* {{flag|Falkland Islands|name=Falkland Islands / Islas Malvinas}}<sup>*</sup> ([[United Kingdom]])\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|French Guiana}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Guyana}}\n* {{flag|Paraguay}}\n* {{flag|Peru}}\n* {{flag|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands}}<sup>*</sup> ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Suriname}}\n* {{flag|Uruguay}}\n* {{flag|Venezuela}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> [[Territorial dispute|Disputed territories]] administered by the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n=== West Indies ===\n{{Main|West Indies}}\n\n==== Caribbean ====\n{{Main|Caribbean}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Anguilla}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}\n* {{flag|Aruba}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bajo Nuevo Bank]]<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Barbados}}\n* {{flag|Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba}} ([[Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|British Virgin Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Cayman Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Cuba}}\n* {{flag|Cura\u00e7ao}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|Dominica}}\n* {{flag|Dominican Republic}}\n* {{flag|Federal Dependencies of Venezuela}}\n* {{flag|Grenada}}\n* {{flag|Guadeloupe}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Haiti}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Jamaica}}\n* {{flag|Martinique}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Montserrat}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Navassa Island}} ([[United States]])\n* {{flag|Nueva Esparta}} ([[Venezuela]])\n* {{flag|Puerto Rico}} ([[United States]])\n* {{flag|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n* {{flag|Saint Lucia}}\n* {{flag|Collectivity of Saint Martin|name=Saint Martin}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n* {{flag|Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina|name=San Andr\u00e9s and Providencia}} ([[Colombia]])\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Serranilla Bank]]<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Sint Maarten}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n* {{flag|United States Virgin Islands}} ([[United States]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> [[Territorial dispute|Disputed territories]] administered by the [[Colombia]].\n\n==== Lucayan Archipelago ====\n{{Main|Lucayan Archipelago}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=200%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Bahamas}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Turks and Caicos Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Somewhat are included===\n{{col-begin|width=115%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Bermuda}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Clipperton Island}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Easter Island}} ([[Chile]])\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Quebec}} ([[Canada]])\n* {{flag|Saint Pierre and Miquelon}} ([[France]])\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Isla Salas y G\u00f3mez|Salas y G\u00f3mez Island]] ([[Chile]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Economy==\nIt is estimated to attribute for over 400 billion dollars that form the core for [[economic stability]], however, few countries, notably [[Venezuela]], are parts of the [[OPEC]].\n\n==Instability==\nThe region has a unique history and varied between stability to instability, included various deadly conflicts, though its level remains conflicted. The two deadliest conflicts in the region are [[Colombian conflict]] and [[Mexican Drug War]]; and more recently, the [[crisis in Venezuela]]. Some other bloody conflicts also include the [[Internal conflict in Peru]] and gang wars in Brazil, Honduras and Argentina. Other conflicts include [[Mapuche conflict]] in Chile and Argentina; and [[Insurgency in Paraguay]]. These conflicts, however, have received lesser attentions from international media, and varied by time, with Colombia in headline in 1990s, Mexico in the 2000s and currently, Venezuela.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Religion===\nMost countries are dominated by [[Christianity]], the largest being [[Roman Catholic]]. Smaller groups include [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodoxy]] and [[Protestantism]].\n\n===Music===\n{{see also|Music of Latin America|List of Caribbean music genres}}\n\nThe region is extremely popular for its own distinct [[music]] which can't be found somewhere in the world. Began since the conquest of Spain, France, Britain, the Netherlands and Portugal in 15th century, due to the greater diversification including indigenous, Asian, African and European population merged together, it expanded popularity of their music, dated from 1950s and rampant globalization, music from the region has become widely noticed, and has been nominated for several music awards.<ref>[https://fas.calendar.utoronto.ca/course/mus305h1 MUS305H1: Latin American and Caribbean Music]</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nThe region is very rich at sporting activites, especially in [[association football]], which have some of the world's strongest football teams like [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], etc; though [[baseball]], [[tennis]], [[cycling]], [[volleyball]], [[rugby union]], [[basketball]], [[hockey]], [[cricket]], also gain recent popularity.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Americas (terminology)]]\n* [[Caribbean]]\n* [[Central America]]\n* [[Community of Latin American and Caribbean States]] (CELAC)\n* [[Latin America]]\n* [[Latin American and Caribbean Group]]\n* [[Latin Americans]]\n* [[North America]]\n* [[Northern America]]\n* [[South America]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme for the Americas]]\n* [[United Nations Statistics Division]] (UNSD)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lac}}\n\n[[Category:Economic country classifications]]\n[[Category:Latin America]]\n[[Category:Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Acronyms]]\n", "text_old": "The term '''Latin America and the Caribbean''' ('''LAC''')<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/new/en/unesco/worldwide/latin-america-and-the-caribbean/ Latin America and the Caribbean]</ref> is an [[English language|English-language]] [[acronym]] referring to the [[Caribbean]] and [[Latin America]] region. The term LAC covers an extensive region, extending from [[Bahamas]] and [[Mexico]] to [[Argentina]] and [[Chile]]. The region consists over 670,230,000 people {{as of|2016|lc=y}}, and spanned for {{convert|21,951,000|km2|sqmi}}.\n\n== List of countries and territories by subregion ==\n=== Central America ===\n{{Main|Central America}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=85%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Belize}}\n* {{flag|Costa Rica}}\n* {{flag|El Salvador}}\n* {{flag|Guatemala}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Honduras}}\n* {{flag|Mexico}}<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Nicaragua}}\n* {{flag|Panama}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> The [[United Nations geoscheme|UN]] includes [[Mexico]] in [[Central America]]<ref>[https://unstats.un.org/unsd/methodology/m49/ UNSD Methodology \u2013 Standard country or area codes for statistical use (M49)]</ref>.\n\n=== South America ===\n{{Main|South America}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Argentina}}\n* {{flag|Bolivia}}\n* {{flag|Bouvet Island}} ([[Norway]])\n* {{flag|Brazil}}\n* {{flag|Chile}}\n* {{flag|Colombia}}\n* {{flag|Ecuador}} (including the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]])\n* {{flag|Falkland Islands|name=Falkland Islands / Islas Malvinas}}<sup>*</sup> ([[United Kingdom]])\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|French Guiana}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Guyana}}\n* {{flag|Paraguay}}\n* {{flag|Peru}}\n* {{flag|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands}}<sup>*</sup> ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Suriname}}\n* {{flag|Uruguay}}\n* {{flag|Venezuela}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> [[Territorial dispute|Disputed territories]] administered by the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n=== West Indies ===\n{{Main|West Indies}}\n\n==== Caribbean ====\n{{Main|Caribbean}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Anguilla}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}\n* {{flag|Aruba}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bajo Nuevo Bank]]<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Barbados}}\n* {{flag|Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba}} ([[Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|British Virgin Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Cayman Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Cuba}}\n* {{flag|Cura\u00e7ao}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|Dominica}}\n* {{flag|Dominican Republic}}\n* {{flag|Federal Dependencies of Venezuela}}\n* {{flag|Grenada}}\n* {{flag|Guadeloupe}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Haiti}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Jamaica}}\n* {{flag|Martinique}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Montserrat}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Navassa Island}} ([[United States]])\n* {{flag|Nueva Esparta}} ([[Venezuela]])\n* {{flag|Puerto Rico}} ([[United States]])\n* {{flag|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n* {{flag|Saint Lucia}}\n* {{flag|Collectivity of Saint Martin|name=Saint Martin}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n* {{flag|Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina|name=San Andr\u00e9s and Providencia}} ([[Colombia]])\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Serranilla Bank]]<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Sint Maarten}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n* {{flag|United States Virgin Islands}} ([[United States]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> [[Territorial dispute|Disputed territories]] administered by the [[Colombia]].\n\n==== Lucayan Archipelago ====\n{{Main|Lucayan Archipelago}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=200%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Bahamas}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Turks and Caicos Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Somewhat are included===\n{{col-begin|width=115%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Bermuda}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Clipperton Island}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Easter Island}} ([[Chile]])\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Quebec}} ([[Canada]])\n* {{flag|Saint Pierre and Miquelon}} ([[France]])\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Isla Salas y G\u00f3mez|Salas y G\u00f3mez Island]] ([[Chile]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Economy==\nIt is estimated to atributte for over 400 bil. dollars that form the core for [[economic stability]], however, few countries, notably [[Venezuela]], are parts of [[OPEC]].\n\n==Instability==\nThe region has a unique history and varied between stability to instability, included various deadly conflicts, though its level remains conflicted. The two deadliest conflicts in the region are [[Colombian conflict]] and [[Mexican Drug War]]; and more recently, the [[crisis in Venezuela]]. Some other bloody conflicts also include the [[Internal conflict in Peru]] and gang wars in Brazil, Honduras and Argentina. Other conflicts include [[Mapuche conflict]] in Chile and Argentina; and [[Insurgency in Paraguay]]. These conflicts, however, have received lesser attentions from international media, and varied by time, with Colombia in headline in 1990s, Mexico in the 2000s and currently, Venezuela.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Religion===\nMost countries are dominated by [[Christianity]], the largest being [[Roman Catholic]]. Smaller groups include [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodoxy]] and [[Protestantism]].\n\n===Music===\n{{see also|Music of Latin America|List of Caribbean music genres}}\n\nThe region is extremely popular for its own distinct [[music]] which can't be found somewhere in the world. Began since the conquest of Spain, France, Britain, the Netherlands and Portugal in 15th century, due to the greater diversification including indigenous, Asian, African and European population merged together, it expanded popularity of their music, dated from 1950s and rampant globalization, music from the region has become widely noticed, and has been nominated for several music awards.<ref>[https://fas.calendar.utoronto.ca/course/mus305h1 MUS305H1: Latin American and Caribbean Music]</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nThe region is very rich at sporting activites, especially in [[association football]], which have some of the world's strongest football teams like [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], etc; though [[baseball]], [[tennis]], [[cycling]], [[volleyball]], [[rugby union]], [[basketball]], [[hockey]], [[cricket]], also gain recent popularity.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Americas (terminology)]]\n* [[Caribbean]]\n* [[Central America]]\n* [[Community of Latin American and Caribbean States]] (CELAC)\n* [[Latin America]]\n* [[Latin American and Caribbean Group]]\n* [[Latin Americans]]\n* [[North America]]\n* [[Northern America]]\n* [[South America]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme for the Americas]]\n* [[United Nations Statistics Division]] (UNSD)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lac}}\n\n[[Category:Economic country classifications]]\n[[Category:Latin America]]\n[[Category:Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Acronyms]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_America_and_the_Caribbean"}
{"title_page": "37mm marsh mortar", "text_new": "The '''37mm marsh mortar''' was a compact [[commando mortar]] developed by the [[Iranian Army]] during the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]. It is very similar in concept to the World War II Soviet [[37mm spade mortar]]. Though not officially designated as ''[[marsh]] mortar'', the term is used by academics in describing this mortar.\n\nThough small for a mortar, 37mm was the maximum shell size for which [[recoil]] did not drive the mortar into the soft [[Soil|ground]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/Janes_Infantry_Weapons/page/n2549 37 mm Marsh mortar] Jane's Infantery Weapons, archived by the [[Internet Archive]]</ref>\n\n==Notes and sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mortars of Iran]]\n[[Category:Infantry mortars]]\n[[Category:37 mm artillery]]\n\n\n{{weapon-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''37mm marsh mortar''' was a compact [[commando mortar]] developed by the [[Iranian Army]] during the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]. It is very similar in concept to the World War II Soviet [[37mm spade mortar]]. Though not officially designated as ''[[marsh]] mortar'', the term is used by academics in describing this mortar.\n\nThough small for a mortar, 37mm was the maximum shell size for which [[recoil]] did not drive the mortar into the soft [[Soil|ground]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/Janes_Infantry_Weapons/page/n2549 37 mm Marsh mortar] Jane's Infantery Weapons, archived by the [[Internet Archive]]</ref>\n\n==Notes and sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Artillery of Iran]]\n[[Category:Infantry mortars]]\n[[Category:37 mm artillery]]\n\n\n{{weapon-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Aldis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes and sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/37mm_marsh_mortar"}
{"title_page": "Raabta (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Raabta\n| image          = Raabta poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| film_name      = \n| director       = [[Dinesh Vijan]]\n| producer       = Dinesh Vijan<br/>[[Homi Adajania]]<br/>[[Bhushan Kumar]]\n| writer         = Siddharth-Garima\n| starring       = [[Sushant Singh Rajput]]<br />[[Kriti Sanon]]<br />[[Jim Sarbh]]<br />[[Varun Sharma]]<br />[[Rajkumar Rao]]\n| narrator       = [[Irrfan]]\n| music          = '''Songs:''' <br /> [[Pritam]] <br /> [[JAM8]] <br /> '''Background Score:''' <br/> [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n| cinematography = Martin Preiss\n| editing        = [[A. Sreekar Prasad]] <br/> Huzefa Lokhandwala\n| studio         = [[Maddock Films]]\n| distributor    = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2017|6|09}}\n| runtime        = 148 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}45 crore<ref>https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=3549</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}39.08 [[crore]]<ref>https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=3549</ref>\n| Website        = https://raabta.net/\n}}\n\n'''''Raabta''''' ({{translation|Connection}}) is a 2017 Indian [[Hindi-language]] [[supernaturalist fiction | supernaturalist]] [[Romance film|romantic]] fiction directed by [[Dinesh Vijan]] in his directorial debut and co-produced by Vijan, [[Homi Adajania]], [[Bhushan Kumar]]. It stars [[Kriti Sanon]] and [[Sushant Singh Rajput]], with [[Jim Sarbh]], [[Rajkumar Yadav]] and [[Varun Sharma]] in supporting roles. The story is based on the concept of [[Reincarnation|reincarnated]] [[star-crossed lovers]]. ''Raabta'' released on 9 June 2017 at a budget of {{INR|450 million}}. It underperformed at the box office, grossing {{INR|398 million}} worldwide, and was termed a \"disaster\" by [[Box Office India]].\n\n==Plot==\nShiv Kakkar ([[Sushant Singh Rajput]]) is a young man from [[Amritsar]] who gets a lucrative opportunity to work in [[Budapest]] for a job as a banker, and lives with his friend, Radha ([[Varun Sharma]]). Shiv is shown to have been a fun-loving womanizer back home and continues this behaviour in Budapest. Saira Singh ([[Kriti Sanon]]), a young woman, is haunted by mysterious nightmares of drowning to death. She lives by herself in Budapest and works as a chocolatier. Shiv happens to stumble upon Saira's shop while on a date with a woman, but finds himself deeply attracted to Saira. Though she initially rejects his advances, she eventually succumbs and sleeps with Shiv, revealing the next day that she actually has a boyfriend and what happened with Shiv was a mistake. Unwilling to let go of their connection, Shiv interrupts Saira's date with her boyfriend Manav ([[Vikas Verma]]) and shows her that she would rather be with him than with her boyfriend. Manav breaks up with her, and Shiv and Saira start spending time together, growing close. One night, they go to a club with Radha, where they happen to meet an eccentric psychic who knows about Saira's nightmares and tells her that the events of her previous life will repeat themselves, and only she can fix them. Saira tearfully reveals to Shiv that she has a fear of water because her parents drowned after a car accident when she was two years old.\n\nWhile trying to test their love a final time, Shiv and Saira make a pact. Shiv flirts with multiple women, but Saira finds herself strongly drawn to a young businessman Zakir \"Zack\" Merchant ([[Jim Sarbh]]). Shiv reveals he has to leave for a business trip for a week and he and Saira decide to see how they feel after a week's separation. If they still feel strongly about each other, they will start considering marriage. During Shiv's absence, Saira gets to know Zakir better and confides in him about her nightmares. During one of their dinners, Zakir drugs Saira and kidnaps her.\n\nSaira wakes up and finds herself trapped in Zakir's isolated mansion on an island off the coast. She demands him to let her go, but he refuses, saying that he spent his whole life looking for her. He explains that he was madly in love with her in a previous life but his love remained unrequited. He refuses to let go of her again. When she does not believe him, he shows her a collection of uncannily accurate paintings he made of her at various ages and says she will find the explanation for her nightmares. Thinking he is crazy, she attempts to escape but ends up falling into the ocean, which triggers the memories of her previous life.\n\nThree hundred years ago, Saira was warrior princess Saiba. She had a childhood best friend Kabir ([[Jim Sarbh]]), a fellow warrior from her tribe who was in love with her. Their kingdom was threatened by the Muraakis, led by a wise, old Rajput ruler Muwwaqqil ([[Rajkummar Rao]]). Qaabir is severely wounded by the fierce warrior Jilaan ([[Sushant Singh Rajput]]), who gives Qaabir an ultimatum to surrender. Saiba challenges Jilaan, and they find themselves attracted to each other. Saiba accepts defeat, surrendering the kingdom to the Muraakis and herself to Jilaan. Qaabir attempts to take Saiba back, but she reveals that she and Jilaan are in love. On their wedding night, a [[comet]] falls and Muwwaqqil realizes that this will be a fateful night. Qaabir ambushes Jilaan and Saiba, and murders Jilaan by wounding him and throws him in the ocean. Saiba jumps into the ocean to save him, but to no avail. Heartbroken on seeing Jilaan die, Saiba who is also heartbroken decides to drown too. On seeing Saiba dead, Qaabir slits his own throat, killing himself. Muwwaqqil forebodes that these events will repeat.\n\nHowever, this time, when Shiv shows up, Saira decides to fight back against Zakir. When their previous lives' events repeat, Zakir throwing Shiv into the ocean, Shiv drags Zakir down with him and Zakir dies. Saira jumps into the water and is able to save Shiv.\n\nThe film ends with Shiv humorously telling their children to not to believe Saira if she tells them any far-fetched stories about reincarnation, implying that he is still oblivious to the events of their previous lives.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sushant Singh Rajput]] as Jilaan/Shiv Kakkar\n* [[Kriti Sanon]] as Saiba/Saira Singh\n* [[Jim Sarbh]] as Kabir/Zakir \"Zak\" Merchant\n* [[Varun Sharma]] as Radha, Shiv's friend\n* [[Vikas Verma]] as Manav Mehta\n* [[Rajkummar Rao]] as Muwwaqqil\n* [[Deepika Padukone]] in a special appearance in the title track\n\n==Production ==\nThe film production began in 2015 and it was set to release in 2016. But the film was delayed for a year due to casting issues. In March 2016, a new release date of 9 June 2017 was announced.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sushant Singh Rajput-Kriti Sanon starrer \u2018Raabta\u2019 goes on floor|url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-starrer-raabta-goes-on-floor-942327/|website=[[India.com]]|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> The film has been majorly shot in&nbsp;[[Budapest]],&nbsp;[[Hungary]] and India. Title song Raabta was shot at [[Tata Castle]] in [[Tata, Hungary|Tata]], Hungary. The song Sadda Move was shot at [[Partition Museum]], [[Amritsar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollylocations.com/movies/Raabta|title=Bollywood Movie Raabta Shooting Locations|website=www.bollylocations.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-05-18}}</ref> Budget of the film is \u20b959.07&nbsp;Crores (\u20b9590.7 Million).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boxofficecollectionreport.com/movies/raabta-box-office-collection-rabta-total-worldwide-business-income|title=Raabta Box Office Collection {{!}} Rabta Total Worldwide Business Income|website=boxofficecollectionreport.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref> The total number of screen count in India was 1820 and 330 overseas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movieboxoffice-collection.com/raabta-total-worldwide-box-office-collection-income-business/|title=Raabta Total Worldwide Box Office Collection Income Business {{!}} Movie Total Box Office Collection, 1st Day Income Business|website=movieboxoffice-collection.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-09}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[Alia Bhatt]] was initially considered to play the lead role opposite [[Sushant Singh Rajput]], but turned down the role over scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\"TOI Bhatt\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/alia-bhatt-bows-out-homi-adajanias-next-opposite-sushant-singh-rajput/|title=Alia Bhatt opts out of Homi Adajania\u2019s next opposite Sushant Singh Rajput|date=3 June 2015|publisher=|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> In December 2015, [[Asin]] was approached to play the lead role opposite Rajput but she turned down the offer because of her decision to not act post marriage. [[Kriti Sanon]] was signed on to play the lead female role in the film in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sushant Singh Rajput, Kriti Sanon starrer, Rajkumar Rao \u2018Raabta\u2019 goes on floor|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-raabta-goes-on-floor/|website=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\n''Raabta'' makers received a legal notice over plagiarism from ''[[Magadheera]]'' [[Film producer|producer]] [[Allu Aravind]]. ''Raabta'' producers offered to show Arvind the film. They also offered to deposit an escrow amount with the court, but Arvind reportedly rejected both.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/magadheera-producer-allu-aravind-withdraws-plea-seeking-stay-on-raabta-s-release/story-3vTTZWCYY6ESlZ3aelOjqL.html|title= Magadheera producer Allu Aravind withdraws plea seeking stay on Raabta\u2019s release|accessdate=June 8, 2017|date= June 8, 2017}}</ref> A source says it was likely Arvind wanted ''Magadheera'' to be remade in Hindi, and was concerned no one would be interested after ''Raabta''.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} On 8 June 2017, the courts ruled in favor of ''Raabta'' makers.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[Bollywood Hungama]] rated it 3.5/5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/raabta/critic-review/|title=Raabta Review - Bollywood Hungama|first=Bollywood|last=Hungama|website=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> [[The Times of India]] rated it 3.5/5, writing \"If sparks flew more organically, it would have been easier to make a connection with this epic tale of love.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/raabta/movie-review/59039834.cms|title=Raabta Review {2.5/5}: If sparks flew more organically, it would have been easier to make a connection with this epic tale of love|website=The Times of India|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> [[Koimoi]] rated it 2/5, writing \"Raabta is a confused film that never establishes a firm balance between its crossover love stories.\" Shubhra Gupta from [[The Indian Express]] rated it 1.5/5, writing \"Some questions arise after Raabta has been seen, chief amongst which is one that comes up every time Bollywood tries, and fails, to do a cracking romance. Why is Bollywood incapable of pulling off a full-length film with a pair of lovers connecting, pulling apart, coming together?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/raabta-movie-review-sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-star-rating-4694804/|title=Raabta movie review: Sushant Singh Rajput, Kriti Sanon film is a rom con|date=9 June 2017|publisher=|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> [[India Today]] rated it 1/5, calling it \"A comet-crossed romance which never hits the target.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/raabta-movie-review-sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon/1/974830.html|title=Raabta movie review: A comet-crossed romance which never hits the target|website=m.indiatoday.in|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nCritic [[Rajeev Masand]] gave the movie one out of five, stating, \"This is a movie so singularly pointless, you have to wonder how the writers and the director tricked the financiers into thinking there was a story here worth telling, and why the actors preferred going to shoot every morning instead of sleeping longer hours. This is the kind of film that film critics must endure so you don\u2019t have to. Even [[Denzel Washington]] couldn't save this film. I\u2019m going with one out of five.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rajeevmasand.com/reviews/our-films/raabish/ |title=Raabish! |publisher=Rajeev Masand|date=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Raabta\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Pritam]], [[JAM8]] and [[Meet Bros]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|2017|06|3}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 30:46\n| language   = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| label      = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Raabta\n | type        = Soundtrack\n | single1     = Ik Vaari Aa\n | single1date = 21 April 2017\n | single2     = Raabta\n | single2date = 2 May 2017\n | single3     = Sadda Move\n | single3date = 9 May 2017\n | single4     = Lambiyaan Si Judaiyaan\n | single4date = 18 May 2017\n | single5     = Main Tera Boyfriend\n | single5date = 22 May 2017\n | single6     = Darasal\n | single6date = 1 June 2017\n}}\n}}\nThe film's music was composed by [[Pritam]], [[JAM8]] and [[Meet Bros]] while lyrics are penned by [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]], [[Irshad Kamil]] and [[Kumaar]]. The first song of the film \"Ik Vaari Aa\" sung by [[Arijit Singh]] was released on 21 April 2017. The second track of the film \"Raabta\" (Title Track) is a remake from 2012 film ''[[Agent Vinod (2012 film)|Agent Vinod]]''{{'}}s \"Raabta (Kehte Hain Khuda)\" by Irshad Kamil, and by original makers Amitabh Bhattacharya and Pritam, sung by Arijit Singh and [[Nikhita Gandhi]] and was released on 2 May 2017. The third song \"Sadda Move\" sung by [[Diljit Dosanjh]] and Pardeep Singh Sran and rapped by [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]] was released on 9 May 2017. The fourth song titled \"Lambiyaan Si Judaiyaan\" sung by Singh, Shadab Faridi and Altamash Faridi was released on 18 May 2017. The fifth track of the film \"[[Main Tera Boyfriend]]\" from J Star's 2015 single \"Na Na Na Na\", originally written by [[Kumaar]] and composed by Sohrabuddin and Sourav Roy was recreated for this film and was released on 22 May 2017. The sixth and the last song titled \"Darasal\" voiced by [[Atif Aslam]] was released on 1 June 2017. Music director [[Pritam]] gave his credit to his launched band [[JAM8]] due to creative differences with producers. He cleared that he wants to work as a solo composer by posting a status on [[Facebook]]. The soundtrack consists of 7 songs and was released on 3 June 2017.\n{{Track_listing\n| headline= Track listing \n| all_music= \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1  = Ik Vaari Aa\n| length1 = 4:34\n| lyrics1 = [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]]\n| music1  = [[Pritam]]\n| extra1  = [[Arijit Singh]]\n| title2  = [[Raabta (song)|Raabta]]\n| length2 = 4:57 \n| lyrics2 = Amitabh Bhattacharya, [[Irshad Kamil]]\n| note2   = Title Track\n| music2  = Pritam\n| extra2  = [[Arijit Singh]], [[Nikhita Gandhi]]\n| title3  = Sadda Move\n| length3 = 3:31\n| lyrics3 = Amitabh Bhattacharya, Irshad Kamil\n| music3  = Pritam\n| extra3  = [[Diljit Dosanjh]], Pardeep Singh Sran, [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]]\n| title4  = Lambiyaan Si Judaiyaan\n| length4 = 3:58\n| lyrics4 = Amitabh Bhattacharya\n| music4  = [[JAM8]]\n| extra4  = Arijit Singh, Shadab Faridi, Altamash Faridi\n| title5  = [[Main Tera Boyfriend]]\n| length5 = 4:36\n| lyrics5 = Kumaar\n| music5  = [[Meet Bros]]\n| extra5  = Arijit Singh, [[Neha Kakkar]], [[Meet Bros]]\n| title6  = Darasal\n| length6 = 4:34\n| lyrics6 = Irshad Kamil\n| music6  = JAM8\n| extra6  = [[Atif Aslam]]\n| title7  = Ik Vaari Aa\n| note7   = Reprise Version\n| music7  = Pritam\n| length7 = 4:34\n| lyrics7 = Amitabh Bhattacharya\n| extra7  = [[Jubin Nautiyal]]\n| total_length = 30:46\n}}\n\n== Box office ==\nBy the opening weekend, the movie collected Rs.15.93 crores nationwide. The lifetime collection of Raabta was Rs.25.67 crores nationwide. The movie made worldwide gross collection of Rs.39.05 crores. It was declared a flop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/raabta/box-office/|title=Raabta Box Office Collection {{!}} Raabta Film Collection {{!}} Box Office Till Now|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|website=Bollywood Hungama|language=en|access-date=2019-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award Ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n! Ref.(s)\n|-\n| [[10th Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Album of The Year|Album of The Year]]\n| [[Pritam]], [[JAM8]], [[Irshad Kamil]], [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]], [[Kumaar]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|title=Nominations - Mirchi Music Awards 2017|website=MMAMirchiMusicAwards|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References  ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n*{{IMDb title|5542802}}\n\n[[Category:T-Series films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Films set in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Films set in Asia]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Indian romance films]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:Romantic action films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Raabta\n| image          = Raabta poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| film_name      = \n| director       = [[Dinesh Vijan]]\n| producer       = Dinesh Vijan<br/>[[Homi Adajania]]<br/>[[Bhushan Kumar]]\n| writer         = Siddharth-Garima\n| starring       = [[Sushant Singh Rajput]]<br />[[Kriti Sanon]]<br />[[Jim Sarbh]]<br />[[Varun Sharma]]<br />[[Rajkumar Rao]]\n| narrator       = [[Irrfan]]\n| music          = '''Songs:''' <br /> [[Pritam]] <br /> [[JAM8]] <br /> '''Background Score:''' <br/> [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n| cinematography = Martin Preiss\n| editing        = [[A. Sreekar Prasad]] <br/> Huzefa Lokhandwala\n| studio         = [[Maddock Films]]\n| distributor    = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2017|6|09}}\n| runtime        = 148 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}45 crore<ref>https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=3549</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}39.08 [[crore]]<ref>https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=3549</ref>\n| Website        = https://raabta.net/\n}}\n\n'''''Raabta''''' ({{translation|Connection}}) is a 2017 Indian [[Hindi-language]] [[supernaturalist fiction | supernaturalist]] [[romantic]] fiction directed by [[Dinesh Vijan]] in his directorial debut and co-produced by Vijan, [[Homi Adajania]], [[Bhushan Kumar]]. It stars [[Kriti Sanon]] and [[Sushant Singh Rajput]], with [[Jim Sarbh]], [[Rajkumar Yadav]] and [[Varun Sharma]] in supporting roles. The story is based on the concept of [[Reincarnation|reincarnated]] [[star-crossed lovers]]. ''Raabta'' released on 9 June 2017 at a budget of {{INR|450 million}}. It underperformed at the box office, grossing {{INR|398 million}} worldwide, and was termed a \"disaster\" by [[Box Office India]].\n\n==Plot==\nShiv Kakkar ([[Sushant Singh Rajput]]) is a young man from [[Amritsar]] who gets a lucrative opportunity to work in [[Budapest]] for a job as a banker, and lives with his friend, Radha ([[Varun Sharma]]). Shiv is shown to have been a fun-loving womanizer back home and continues this behaviour in Budapest. Saira Singh ([[Kriti Sanon]]), a young woman, is haunted by mysterious nightmares of drowning to death. She lives by herself in Budapest and works as a chocolatier. Shiv happens to stumble upon Saira's shop while on a date with a woman, but finds himself deeply attracted to Saira. Though she initially rejects his advances, she eventually succumbs and sleeps with Shiv, revealing the next day that she actually has a boyfriend and what happened with Shiv was a mistake. Unwilling to let go of their connection, Shiv interrupts Saira's date with her boyfriend Manav ([[Vikas Verma]]) and shows her that she would rather be with him than with her boyfriend. Manav breaks up with her, and Shiv and Saira start spending time together, growing close. One night, they go to a club with Radha, where they happen to meet an eccentric psychic who knows about Saira's nightmares and tells her that the events of her previous life will repeat themselves, and only she can fix them. Saira tearfully reveals to Shiv that she has a fear of water because her parents drowned after a car accident when she was two years old.\n\nWhile trying to test their love a final time, Shiv and Saira make a pact. Shiv flirts with multiple women, but Saira finds herself strongly drawn to a young businessman Zakir \"Zack\" Merchant ([[Jim Sarbh]]). Shiv reveals he has to leave for a business trip for a week and he and Saira decide to see how they feel after a week's separation. If they still feel strongly about each other, they will start considering marriage. During Shiv's absence, Saira gets to know Zakir better and confides in him about her nightmares. During one of their dinners, Zakir drugs Saira and kidnaps her.\n\nSaira wakes up and finds herself trapped in Zakir's isolated mansion on an island off the coast. She demands him to let her go, but he refuses, saying that he spent his whole life looking for her. He explains that he was madly in love with her in a previous life but his love remained unrequited. He refuses to let go of her again. When she does not believe him, he shows her a collection of uncannily accurate paintings he made of her at various ages and says she will find the explanation for her nightmares. Thinking he is crazy, she attempts to escape but ends up falling into the ocean, which triggers the memories of her previous life.\n\nThree hundred years ago, Saira was warrior princess Saiba. She had a childhood best friend Kabir ([[Jim Sarbh]]), a fellow warrior from her tribe who was in love with her. Their kingdom was threatened by the Muraakis, led by a wise, old Rajput ruler Muwwaqqil ([[Rajkummar Rao]]). Qaabir is severely wounded by the fierce warrior Jilaan ([[Sushant Singh Rajput]]), who gives Qaabir an ultimatum to surrender. Saiba challenges Jilaan, and they find themselves attracted to each other. Saiba accepts defeat, surrendering the kingdom to the Muraakis and herself to Jilaan. Qaabir attempts to take Saiba back, but she reveals that she and Jilaan are in love. On their wedding night, a [[comet]] falls and Muwwaqqil realizes that this will be a fateful night. Qaabir ambushes Jilaan and Saiba, and murders Jilaan by wounding him and throws him in the ocean. Saiba jumps into the ocean to save him, but to no avail. Heartbroken on seeing Jilaan die, Saiba who is also heartbroken decides to drown too. On seeing Saiba dead, Qaabir slits his own throat, killing himself. Muwwaqqil forebodes that these events will repeat.\n\nHowever, this time, when Shiv shows up, Saira decides to fight back against Zakir. When their previous lives' events repeat, Zakir throwing Shiv into the ocean, Shiv drags Zakir down with him and Zakir dies. Saira jumps into the water and is able to save Shiv.\n\nThe film ends with Shiv humorously telling their children to not to believe Saira if she tells them any far-fetched stories about reincarnation, implying that he is still oblivious to the events of their previous lives.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sushant Singh Rajput]] as Jilaan/Shiv Kakkar\n* [[Kriti Sanon]] as Saiba/Saira Singh\n* [[Jim Sarbh]] as Kabir/Zakir \"Zak\" Merchant\n* [[Varun Sharma]] as Radha, Shiv's friend\n* [[Vikas Verma]] as Manav Mehta\n* [[Rajkummar Rao]] as Muwwaqqil\n* [[Deepika Padukone]] in a special appearance in the title track\n\n==Production ==\nThe film production began in 2015 and it was set to release in 2016. But the film was delayed for a year due to casting issues. In March 2016, a new release date of 9 June 2017 was announced.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sushant Singh Rajput-Kriti Sanon starrer \u2018Raabta\u2019 goes on floor|url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-starrer-raabta-goes-on-floor-942327/|website=[[India.com]]|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> The film has been majorly shot in&nbsp;[[Budapest]],&nbsp;[[Hungary]] and India. Title song Raabta was shot at [[Tata Castle]] in [[Tata, Hungary|Tata]], Hungary. The song Sadda Move was shot at [[Partition Museum]], [[Amritsar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollylocations.com/movies/Raabta|title=Bollywood Movie Raabta Shooting Locations|website=www.bollylocations.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-05-18}}</ref> Budget of the film is \u20b959.07&nbsp;Crores (\u20b9590.7 Million).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boxofficecollectionreport.com/movies/raabta-box-office-collection-rabta-total-worldwide-business-income|title=Raabta Box Office Collection {{!}} Rabta Total Worldwide Business Income|website=boxofficecollectionreport.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref> The total number of screen count in India was 1820 and 330 overseas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movieboxoffice-collection.com/raabta-total-worldwide-box-office-collection-income-business/|title=Raabta Total Worldwide Box Office Collection Income Business {{!}} Movie Total Box Office Collection, 1st Day Income Business|website=movieboxoffice-collection.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-09}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[Alia Bhatt]] was initially considered to play the lead role opposite [[Sushant Singh Rajput]], but turned down the role over scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\"TOI Bhatt\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/alia-bhatt-bows-out-homi-adajanias-next-opposite-sushant-singh-rajput/|title=Alia Bhatt opts out of Homi Adajania\u2019s next opposite Sushant Singh Rajput|date=3 June 2015|publisher=|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> In December 2015, [[Asin]] was approached to play the lead role opposite Rajput but she turned down the offer because of her decision to not act post marriage. [[Kriti Sanon]] was signed on to play the lead female role in the film in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sushant Singh Rajput, Kriti Sanon starrer, Rajkumar Rao \u2018Raabta\u2019 goes on floor|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-raabta-goes-on-floor/|website=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\n''Raabta'' makers received a legal notice over plagiarism from ''[[Magadheera]]'' [[Film producer|producer]] [[Allu Aravind]]. ''Raabta'' producers offered to show Arvind the film. They also offered to deposit an escrow amount with the court, but Arvind reportedly rejected both.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/magadheera-producer-allu-aravind-withdraws-plea-seeking-stay-on-raabta-s-release/story-3vTTZWCYY6ESlZ3aelOjqL.html|title= Magadheera producer Allu Aravind withdraws plea seeking stay on Raabta\u2019s release|accessdate=June 8, 2017|date= June 8, 2017}}</ref> A source says it was likely Arvind wanted ''Magadheera'' to be remade in Hindi, and was concerned no one would be interested after ''Raabta''.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} On 8 June 2017, the courts ruled in favor of ''Raabta'' makers.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[Bollywood Hungama]] rated it 3.5/5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/raabta/critic-review/|title=Raabta Review - Bollywood Hungama|first=Bollywood|last=Hungama|website=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> [[The Times of India]] rated it 3.5/5, writing \"If sparks flew more organically, it would have been easier to make a connection with this epic tale of love.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/raabta/movie-review/59039834.cms|title=Raabta Review {2.5/5}: If sparks flew more organically, it would have been easier to make a connection with this epic tale of love|website=The Times of India|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> [[Koimoi]] rated it 2/5, writing \"Raabta is a confused film that never establishes a firm balance between its crossover love stories.\" Shubhra Gupta from [[The Indian Express]] rated it 1.5/5, writing \"Some questions arise after Raabta has been seen, chief amongst which is one that comes up every time Bollywood tries, and fails, to do a cracking romance. Why is Bollywood incapable of pulling off a full-length film with a pair of lovers connecting, pulling apart, coming together?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/raabta-movie-review-sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-star-rating-4694804/|title=Raabta movie review: Sushant Singh Rajput, Kriti Sanon film is a rom con|date=9 June 2017|publisher=|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> [[India Today]] rated it 1/5, calling it \"A comet-crossed romance which never hits the target.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/raabta-movie-review-sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon/1/974830.html|title=Raabta movie review: A comet-crossed romance which never hits the target|website=m.indiatoday.in|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nCritic [[Rajeev Masand]] gave the movie one out of five, stating, \"This is a movie so singularly pointless, you have to wonder how the writers and the director tricked the financiers into thinking there was a story here worth telling, and why the actors preferred going to shoot every morning instead of sleeping longer hours. This is the kind of film that film critics must endure so you don\u2019t have to. Even [[Denzel Washington]] couldn't save this film. I\u2019m going with one out of five.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rajeevmasand.com/reviews/our-films/raabish/ |title=Raabish! |publisher=Rajeev Masand|date=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Raabta\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Pritam]], [[JAM8]] and [[Meet Bros]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|2017|06|3}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 30:46\n| language   = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| label      = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Raabta\n | type        = Soundtrack\n | single1     = Ik Vaari Aa\n | single1date = 21 April 2017\n | single2     = Raabta\n | single2date = 2 May 2017\n | single3     = Sadda Move\n | single3date = 9 May 2017\n | single4     = Lambiyaan Si Judaiyaan\n | single4date = 18 May 2017\n | single5     = Main Tera Boyfriend\n | single5date = 22 May 2017\n | single6     = Darasal\n | single6date = 1 June 2017\n}}\n}}\nThe film's music was composed by [[Pritam]], [[JAM8]] and [[Meet Bros]] while lyrics are penned by [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]], [[Irshad Kamil]] and [[Kumaar]]. The first song of the film \"Ik Vaari Aa\" sung by [[Arijit Singh]] was released on 21 April 2017. The second track of the film \"Raabta\" (Title Track) is a remake from 2012 film ''[[Agent Vinod (2012 film)|Agent Vinod]]''{{'}}s \"Raabta (Kehte Hain Khuda)\" by Irshad Kamil, and by original makers Amitabh Bhattacharya and Pritam, sung by Arijit Singh and [[Nikhita Gandhi]] and was released on 2 May 2017. The third song \"Sadda Move\" sung by [[Diljit Dosanjh]] and Pardeep Singh Sran and rapped by [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]] was released on 9 May 2017. The fourth song titled \"Lambiyaan Si Judaiyaan\" sung by Singh, Shadab Faridi and Altamash Faridi was released on 18 May 2017. The fifth track of the film \"[[Main Tera Boyfriend]]\" from J Star's 2015 single \"Na Na Na Na\", originally written by [[Kumaar]] and composed by Sohrabuddin and Sourav Roy was recreated for this film and was released on 22 May 2017. The sixth and the last song titled \"Darasal\" voiced by [[Atif Aslam]] was released on 1 June 2017. Music director [[Pritam]] gave his credit to his launched band [[JAM8]] due to creative differences with producers. He cleared that he wants to work as a solo composer by posting a status on [[Facebook]]. The soundtrack consists of 7 songs and was released on 3 June 2017.\n{{Track_listing\n| headline= Track listing \n| all_music= \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1  = Ik Vaari Aa\n| length1 = 4:34\n| lyrics1 = [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]]\n| music1  = [[Pritam]]\n| extra1  = [[Arijit Singh]]\n| title2  = [[Raabta (song)|Raabta]]\n| length2 = 4:57 \n| lyrics2 = Amitabh Bhattacharya, [[Irshad Kamil]]\n| note2   = Title Track\n| music2  = Pritam\n| extra2  = [[Arijit Singh]], [[Nikhita Gandhi]]\n| title3  = Sadda Move\n| length3 = 3:31\n| lyrics3 = Amitabh Bhattacharya, Irshad Kamil\n| music3  = Pritam\n| extra3  = [[Diljit Dosanjh]], Pardeep Singh Sran, [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]]\n| title4  = Lambiyaan Si Judaiyaan\n| length4 = 3:58\n| lyrics4 = Amitabh Bhattacharya\n| music4  = [[JAM8]]\n| extra4  = Arijit Singh, Shadab Faridi, Altamash Faridi\n| title5  = [[Main Tera Boyfriend]]\n| length5 = 4:36\n| lyrics5 = Kumaar\n| music5  = [[Meet Bros]]\n| extra5  = Arijit Singh, [[Neha Kakkar]], [[Meet Bros]]\n| title6  = Darasal\n| length6 = 4:34\n| lyrics6 = Irshad Kamil\n| music6  = JAM8\n| extra6  = [[Atif Aslam]]\n| title7  = Ik Vaari Aa\n| note7   = Reprise Version\n| music7  = Pritam\n| length7 = 4:34\n| lyrics7 = Amitabh Bhattacharya\n| extra7  = [[Jubin Nautiyal]]\n| total_length = 30:46\n}}\n\n== Box office ==\nBy the opening weekend, the movie collected Rs.15.93 crores nationwide. The lifetime collection of Raabta was Rs.25.67 crores nationwide. The movie made worldwide gross collection of Rs.39.05 crores. It was declared a flop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/raabta/box-office/|title=Raabta Box Office Collection {{!}} Raabta Film Collection {{!}} Box Office Till Now|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|website=Bollywood Hungama|language=en|access-date=2019-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award Ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n! Ref.(s)\n|-\n| [[10th Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Album of The Year|Album of The Year]]\n| [[Pritam]], [[JAM8]], [[Irshad Kamil]], [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]], [[Kumaar]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|title=Nominations - Mirchi Music Awards 2017|website=MMAMirchiMusicAwards|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References  ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n*{{IMDb title|5542802}}\n\n[[Category:T-Series films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Films set in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Films set in Asia]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Indian romance films]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:Romantic action films]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.or