{"title_page": "Beat Saber", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Beat Saber\n| image = Beat Saber logo.jpg\n| developer = Beat Games\n| publisher = Beat Games\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Oculus VR]]\n| released = May 21, 2019\n| genre = [[Rhythm game|Rhythm]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n| designer = {{Unbulleted list|J\u00e1n Ilavsk\u00fd|Vladim\u00edr Hrin\u010d\u00e1r|Peter Hrin\u010d\u00e1r}}\n| artist = Jan Ilavsk\u00fd\n| composer = [[Jaroslav Beck]]\n}}\n\n'''''Beat Saber''''' is a [[virtual reality]] [[rhythm game|rhythm game]] developed and published by Beat Games. The game takes place in a surrealistic [[neon noir]] environment and features the player slicing blocks representing musical beats with a pair of contrasting colored sabers. Following an [[early access]] release in November 2018, the game was fully released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Microsoft Windows]] on May 21, 2019. The game supports most [[virtual reality headset]]s, such as [[PlayStation VR]], [[HTC Vive]], [[Oculus Rift]], and [[Oculus Quest]].\n\n== Gameplay ==\nIn Beat Saber, you assume the role of a person wielding two 'sabers'. The goal of the game is to cut blocks in a certain direction, to the beat of a selected song. If you miss multiple blocks, you fail. In the bottom left corner of the screen, you can see your grade. SS is the highest grade, while E is the lowest. The goal is to get a high grade. />\n\nSince its early access stages, the game included a single player mode as well as a party mode, which features a leaderboard with the player's names, which are entered after each song is played. Additionally, the 1.0 release version introduced a level editor and a practice mode which allows the player to alter the song's speed, or start playing it from some point in time other than the beginning, as well as custom songs.\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Beat saber team gdca 2019.jpg|thumb|left|L-R: programmer Vladimir \"Loki\" Hrin\u010d\u00e1r, head of marketing Michaela Dvo\u0159\u00e1kov\u00e1, and composer [[Jaroslav Beck]] at the Game Developers Choice Awards 2019]]\nThe game was first released in [[early access]] on [[Microsoft Windows]] on May 1, 2018.<ref name=\"Windows Central Beat Saber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.windowscentral.com/beat-saber-everything-we-know-about-vr-rhythm-game|title=Beat Saber: Everything we know about the VR rhythm game|last=Hunt|first=Cale|date=April 5, 2018|website=Windows Central|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> The game was released on PlayStation 4 on November 20, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.playstation.com/en-ca/games/beat-saber-ps4/|title=Beat Saber|website=PlayStation|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> An editor was announced for release in May 2018, which would allow for the creation of custom user songs, but it was postponed,<ref name=\"Beat Saber Level Editor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/vr-rhythm-game-beat-saber-now-the-highest-rated-game-on-steam-releasing-level-editor-next-week/|title=VR rhythm game Beat Saber, now the highest rated game on Steam, releasing level editor next week|last=Horti|first=Samuel|date=May 6, 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> and added in May 2019.<ref name=\"RPS 2019-05-21\" />\n\nIn March 2019, Beat Games released its first paid [[downloadable content|song pack]], featuring 10 songs from electronic music record label [[Monstercat]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/beat-saber-releases-first-paid-dlc-song-pack-contains-10-tracks/|title=Beat Saber releases first paid DLC music pack|last=Horti|first=Samuel|date=March 16, 2019|magazine=[[PC Gamer]]|access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> \"[[Crab Rave]]\" was added as a free update on [[April Fools' day]] that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2019/04/01/crab-rave-beat-saber-free-song/|title=Crab Rave is the Latest Free Beat Saber Song, Available Now|date=April 1, 2019|website=PlayStation LifeStyle|access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref> On May 2, 2019, to celebrate the game's first anniversary, a prototype version created three years prior was released to the public as ''Beat Saber Origins''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techmoneyfit.com/blog/beat-saber-releases-origins-early-build-to-celebrate-first-anniversary/|title=Beat Saber Releases Origins Early Build To Celebrate First Anniversary|date=March 4, 2019|website=techmoneyfit.com|access-date=May 10, 2019}}</ref> The game was fully released out of early access on PC on May 21, 2019.<ref name=\"RPS 2019-05-21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/05/22/beat-saber-out/|title=Beat Saber bops out of early access|first=Matt|last=Cox|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019|work=[[Rock Paper Shotgun]]}}</ref> On January 29, 2020, the game received a free pack featuring three songs by Japanese artist Camellia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uploadvr.com/beat-saber-new-track/|title=Three New Free Beat Saber Songs Arrive In New Update From Cametek|date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2019, [[Facebook, Inc.]] via [[Oculus Studios]] announced that it had acquired Beat Games. The company stated that the purchase would not affect future development of ''Beat Saber'' on third-party VR platforms besides Oculus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/26/20984468/facebook-acquisition-beat-games-beat-saber-vr-studio|title=Facebook is buying Beat Saber\u2019s development studio|last=Robertson|first=Adi|date=2019-11-26|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> Beat Games will continue to operate in [[Prague]] as an independent studio, although under the umbrella of Oculus Studios. The studio confirmed that the game's 360 degree mode would maintain its expected release timeframe of December 2019.<ref name=\"CitationA\">{{Citation |last=Holt |first=Kris |date=November 26, 2019 |title=Facebook buys 'Beat Saber' creator Beat Games |publisher= |url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/11/26/oculus-vr-beat-saber/ |accessdate=November 27, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = PS4: 86/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/beat-saber|title=Beat Saber for PlayStation 4 Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><br />PC: 93/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/beat-saber|title=Beat Saber for PC Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| Edge = 8/10<ref name=\"Edge Review\" />\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"GameSpot Review\" />\n| IGN = 9.5/10<ref name=\"IGN Review\" />\n}}\n\nDuring its [[early access]] phase, ''Beat Saber'' received positive reviews, becoming the highest rated game on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] less than a week after its early access release.<ref name=\"Beat Saber Level Editor\" /> The game sold over a million copies by March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Princ|first1=Zden\u011bk|title=Beat Saber p\u0159ekonal hranici milionu prodan\u00fdch kus\u016f|url=https://www.vortex.cz/beat-saber-prekonal-hranici-milionu-prodanych-kusu/|website=www.vortex.cz|publisher=Vortex|accessdate=March 15, 2019|language=Czech}}</ref>\n\n''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' thought the game was an excellent fit for VR as a medium, writing \"At this point in virtual reality's development, it's still rare to encounter a game that feels native to the technology. ''Beat Saber'' is an exception.\"<ref name=\"Edge Review\">{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line--> |title=Beat Saber Review |journal=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |issue=328|publisher=[[Future plc|Future]] |pages=120|date=February 2019}}</ref>\n''[[IGN]]'' noted that while the game \"doesn't push the limits of [VR tech] too far\", the game is extremely effective at communicating the appeal of VR, and considered the game \"a go-to for introducing anyone to virtual reality.\"<ref name=\"IGN Review\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/05/28/beat-saber-review |title=Beat Saber Review |last=Stapleton |first=Dan |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=May 28, 2019 |accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n''[[Gamespot]]'' noted that at launch the supported song library was \"slim\", but nevertheless concluded that \"''Beat Saber'' is an exhilarating rush and an exhausting game to play in the best way.\"<ref name=\"GameSpot Review\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/beat-saber-review-bass-boosted/1900-6417044/ |title=Beat Saber Review \u2013 Bass-Boosted |last=Barbosa |first=Alessandro |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=November 26, 2018 |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| [[The Game Awards 2018]]\n| Best VR/AR Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/game-awards-tga/2018/12/6/18130000/the-game-awards-winners-2018|title=The Game Awards 2018: Here are all the winners|last=Grant|first=Christopher|date=December 6, 2018|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Gamers' Choice Awards]]\n| Fan Favorite VR Game\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerschoice.tv/index.aspx|title=2018 Gamers' Choice Awards|website=[[Gamers' Choice Awards]]|date=December 9, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"20\" | 2019\n| New York Game Awards\n| Coney Island Dreamland Award for Best Virtual Reality Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/2018-new-york-game-awards-nominees/|title=2018 New York Game Awards Nominees Revealed|last=Keyes|first=Rob|date=January 3, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Immersive Reality Technical Achievement\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/god-of-war-spider-man-lead-dice-awards-heres-all-t/1100-6464345/|title=God Of War, Spider-Man Lead DICE Awards; Here's All The Nominees|last=Makuch|first=Eddie|date=January 10, 2019|website=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/2/14/18224190/dice-awards-2019-winners-god-of-war-ps4|title=God of War wins big at DICE Awards 2019|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Immersive Reality Game of the Year\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[NAVGTR]] Awards\n| Game, Music or Performance-Based\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navgtr.org/2019/03/13/winner-list-for-2018-god-of-war-breaks-record/|title=Winner list for 2018: God of War breaks record|website=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]|date=March 13, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Sound Mixing in Virtual Reality\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[SXSW Gaming Awards]]\n| Excellence in Gameplay\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://gaming.sxsw.com/news/2019/2019-sxsw-gaming-awards-finalists/|title=Here Are Your 2019 SXSW Gaming Awards Finalists!|last=Trent|first=Logan|date=February 11, 2019|website=[[South by Southwest]]|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2019/03/17/sxsw-gaming-awards-winners-2019/#/slide/1|title=God of War Takes Home \u2018Game of the Year\u2019 at SXSW 2019 Gaming Awards|last=Khan|first=Zarmena|date=March 17, 2019|website=PlayStation LifeStyle|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Most Promising New Intellectual Property\n| {{Won}}\