P1]]\n| 1994\u20132009\n| ''[[\u015amiechu \u015amiechu Warte]]''\n|-\n| {{ESP}}\n| [[TVE1]]\n| 1990\u20131998\n| ''[[Videos Videos de Primera]]''\n|-\n| {{SWE}}\n| [[TV3 (Sweden)|TV3]]\n| 1991\u20131997\n| ''[[L\u00e5t L\u00e5t kameran g\u00e5]]''\n|-\n| {{GBR}}\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| 1990 \u2013 present\n| ''[[You've Been Framed!]]\n|-\n| {{AUS}}\n| [[Nine Network]]\n| 1990\u20132014\n| ''[[Australia's Funniest Home Videos]]''\n|-\n| {{FRA}}\n| [[TF1]]\n| 1990\u20132008\n| ''[[Video Gag]]''\n|-\n| {{NLD}}\n| [[TROS]]\n| 1990\u20132004\n| ''[[De De Leukste Thuis]]''\n|-\n| {{BEL}}\n| [[VTM (TV channel)|VTM]]\n| 1990\u20132004\n| ''[[Videodinges Videodinges]]''\n|-\n| {{NLD}}\n| [[SBS 6]]\n| 2002 \u2013 present\n| ''[[Lachen Lachen om Home Video's]]''\n|-\n|}-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0098740|title=America's Funniest Home Videos}}\n* {{tv.com show|americas-funniest-home-videos|America's Funniest Home Videos}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070603065822/http://www.shoutfactory.com/browse/5/americas_funniest_home_videos.aspx America's Funniest Home Videos] page from [[Shout! Factory]]\n* {{Official website|http://www.afv.com}}\n\n{{ABCNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n[[Category:1989 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980s American comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Japanese television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=September 2015}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name     = America's Funniest Home Videos\n| image         = AFHV new logo (main).png\n| caption       = Current version of logo, used for the Alfonso Ribeiro era since 2015\n| genre         = [[Clip show]]<br/>[[Comedy]]\n| creator       = [[Vin Di Bona]]\n| based_on      = ''[[Fun TV with Kato-chan and Ken-chan]]''\n| writer        = {{unbulleted list|Mike Palleschi|Erik Lohla|Jordan Schatz}}<br />{{Hidden begin|title=Past writers:}}\n{{unbulleted list|[[Todd Thicke]]|Robert Arnott|Bob Saget|[[Trace Beaulieu]]|[[J. Elvis Weinstein]]|Joel Madison|Tony De Sena|Arthur F. Montmorency|Kevin Kataoka}}\n{{Hidden end}}\n| director                 = Vin Di Bona<br />{{Hidden begin|title=Other directors:}}\n{{unbulleted list|Ron de Moraes|Steve Hirsen|Rob Katz|E.C. Pauling|Averill Perry|Russ Reinsel}}\n{{Hidden end}}\n| presenter                = {{unbulleted list|[[Bob Saget]]|[[John Fugelsang]] & [[Daisy Fuentes]]|[[Tom Bergeron]]|[[Alfonso Ribeiro]]}}\n| narrated                 = {{unbulleted list|[[Ernie Anderson]]|[[Gary Owens]]|[[Jess Harnell]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = Dan Slider (music)<br />[[Jill Colucci]], Stewart Harris (lyrics, 1989\u201396 version only)\n| opentheme                = \"The Funny Things You Do\", <br />performed by Jill Colucci, Peter Hix & Terry Wood,<br />Rearranged ska/reggae instrumental,<br/>Rearranged band instrumental\n| composer                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 30\n| num_episodes             = 698 <!-- as of March 29, 2020 -->\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{unbulleted list|Vin Di Bona|Michele Nasraway|[[Todd Thicke]]}}\n| producer                 = Bill Barlow\n| camera                   = [[Videotape]]; [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]<br />(studio segments)\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes (1990\u201399)<br />44 minutes (1989 and 1999\u20132000 specials; series: 2001\u2013present)\n| company                  = [[ABC Entertainment]]<br />[[Vin Di Bona Productions]]\n| distributor              = {{unbulleted list|[[MTM Enterprises]] (1995\u201397)<br />[[20th Television]] (1998\u20132001)<br />[[Disney-ABC Domestic Television|Buena Vista Television]] (2001\u201307)<br />[[Disney-ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution]] (2007\u2013present)}}\n| network                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080p]] <br />\n<br />[[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br />(home videos [[Video scaler|upscaled]] to [[widescreen]] from seasons 1\u201320)<br />(1989\u20132010)<br />[[720p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])<br />(2010\u2013present)\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1989|11|26}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| related                  = ''[[America's Funniest People]]'' (1990\u201394)<br />''[[World's Funniest Videos]]'' (1996)<br>El Diablito (from [[XHDRBZ]])<br>''[[Videos After Dark]]'' (2019\u2013present)\n| website                  = http://www.afv.com\n| production_website       = http://abc.go.com/shows/americas-funniest-home-videos\n}}\n'''''America's Funniest Home Videos''''' (abbreviated as '''''AFHV''''' and '''''AFV''''') is an American video clip television series on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], which features humorous homemade videos that are submitted by viewers. The most common videos feature unintentional [[physical comedy]], pets or children and some staged [[practical joke|prank]]s. Originally airing as a [[television special|special]] in 1989, it later debuted as a regular weekly series in 1990. The show was hosted by [[Bob Saget]] for the 1989 special and the first eight seasons of the series incarnation. After Saget's retirement from hosting in 1997, [[John Fugelsang]] and [[Daisy Fuentes]] later took over as co-host for its ninth and tenth seasons. After two years of being shown as occasional specials, hosted by various actors and comedians such as [[D.L. Hughley]] and [[Richard Kind]], ABC brought the series back on Friday nights in 2001 with new host [[Tom Bergeron]], who has since become the series' longest-serving host, hosting 15 seasons. Bergeron announced in 2014 that he would be leaving as host of the show, and [[Alfonso Ribeiro]] took over as host in 2015. On October 29, 2018, ABC renewed ''AFV'' for two more seasons, bringing to its 30th (which premiered on Sunday, September 29, 2019) and 31st seasons.\n\n==Premise==\nAFV is based on the [[Tokyo Broadcasting System]] program ''[[Fun TV with Kato-chan and Ken-chan]],'' which featured a segment in which viewers were invited to send in [[video clip]]s from their [[home movies]]; ABC, which owns half the program, pays a royalty fee to the Tokyo Broadcasting System for the use of the format (although the original parent show left the air in 1992).<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-18306720.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105171457/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-18306720.html|archive-date=November 5, 2012|author=Littleton, Cynthia|title=Putting the fun in 'Home Videos'; Vincent John Di Bona, executive producer of television program ''America's Funniest Home Videos''|journal=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|date=May 20, 1996|access-date=March 7, 2011|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> Contestants can submit their videos by uploading them on the show's official website, AFV.com, on the AFV applications for Android or iOS or on the AFV Official Facebook fan page, or by sending them via mail to a [[Hollywood, California]] [[post-office box]] address.<ref name=\"afv.com\" /> The majority of the video clips are short (5\u201330 seconds) and are mostly related to the host's monologues. Videos usually feature people and animals getting into humorous accidents caught on camera; while others include clever marriage proposals, people and animals displaying interesting talents (such as pets that sound like they speak certain words or phrases, or genius toddlers with the ability to name all past [[President of the United States|U.S. Presidents]]), and [[practical joke]]s. A group of screeners view the submitted tapes, giving them a grade (on a scale of 1\u201310) based on that particular tape's humor. The videos deemed the funniest by the screeners then go on to the show's producers and then is turned over to Di Bona and another producer for final approval.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8162596.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106120124/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8162596.html|archive-date=November 6, 2012|author=Susan Bickelhaupt, Globe Staff|title='Funniest Home Videos' Outstrips '60 Minutes'|agency=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=February 28, 1990|access-date=March 7, 2011|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> Home video material that involves staged accidents, or/and adults, children, or babies getting seriously injured or the abuse of animals, or overall does not meet ABC network [[standards and practices]] are generally not accepted and will not appear on the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3995728.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106120132/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3995728.html|archive-date=November 6, 2012|author=Ernest Tucker|title=Saget aims to clip hurtful video bits|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=April 27, 1990|access-date=March 7, 2011|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> Every week, the producers choose three videos that the studio audience will vote on. The winner wins $10,000 and is in the running for the $100,000 prize at the end of a block of episodes, while the runner-up receives $3,000 and the third place video receives $2,000. The winners of the $100,000 prize then compete for a grand prize, supplied by [[Adventures by Disney]].<ref name=\"afv.com\" /> The program's studio segments are taped in front of a studio audience (although the specials that aired in 1999 and 2000 only featured pre-recorded audience responses). Audience members are asked to dress in \"[[business casual]] or nicer.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Bergeron Dishes on the 'America's Funniest Home Videos' Dress Code|url=http://www.parade.com/celebrity/personality-parade/2012/03/25/tom-bergeron.html|periodical=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|publisher=Athlon Publishing|date=March 25, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nShow creator Vin Di Bona has produced two similar programs: ''[[America's Funniest People]]'' (1990\u201394) and ''[[World's Funniest Videos]]'' (1996).<ref>{{Cite pressrelease|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970103033848/http://www.chch.com/press/archive/2ndnoah.htm |title=Two All-New Television Series Premiere on CHCH-TV! |archivedate=January 3, 1997 |date=January 17, 1996 |accessdate=March 12, 2012 |publisher=Niagara Television Limited|url-status=dead|url=http://www.chch.com/press/archive/2ndnoah.htm}}</ref> Di Bona also created the syndicated series ''[[That's Funny]]'', featuring home videos that were largely culled from those seen on ''AFHV'' and ''America's Funniest People'':  (2004\u201306)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-113230359.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106120150/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-113230359.html|archive-date=November 6, 2012|last=Dempsey|first=John|title=Di Bona's 'Funny' will get gags gig|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]]|date=January 23, 2004|access-date=March 7, 2011|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> In 2019, Di Bona also created a [[Spinoff (television)|spinoff]] ''[[Videos After Dark]]'' with more adult material.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bob Saget Returns to ABC for 'Videos After Dark', 'AFV' Renewed Through Season 31|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/bob-saget-returns-abc-videos-dark-afv-renewed-1155870|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=October 30, 2018}}</ref> Several local television stations, even those not affiliated with ABC, also developed special funny home video segments in their newscasts during the early 1990s, inspired by the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3995573.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106120113/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3995573.html|archive-date=November 6, 2012|author=Scott Williams|title=Local TV getting into 'Funniest Videos' act|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=April 26, 1990|access-date=March 8, 2011|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> As noted in the closing credits of each episode, most of the videos have been edited for length due to time constraints. In addition, according to the contest plugs, family members (both immediate or relatives) of employees of [[Vin Di Bona Productions]], [[ABC, Inc.]], its corporate parent [[The Walt Disney Company]] (and for a good portion of Saget's hosting tenure, its legal predecessor, Capital Cities/ABC) and their related subsidiaries are ineligible for the show's contests and prizes. On October 3, 2010, beginning with the show's 21st season premiere,<ref name=\"thefutoncritic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/americas-funniest-home-videos/ |title=Shows A-Z&nbsp;\u2014 america's funniest home videos on abc |publisher=TheFutonCritic.com |date= |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> ''America's Funniest Home Videos'' began broadcasting in [[high-definition television|high definition]]. Many of the videos, which are largely shot using [[standard-definition television|standard definition]] camcorders, began to be [[Stretch-o-Vision|stretched horizontally]] to fit [[16:9]] screens. However, since the 2012\u201313 season, videos shot in 4:3 standard definition began to be [[pillarbox]]ed (particularly videos that are recorded on mobile devices that are shot at a vertical angle that would not even fit the 4:3 [[safe area (television)|safe area]] of many television sets entirely; since the conversion to HD, the series has featured advisories to viewers to tilt their mobile devices horizontally to when recording in order for their videos to fit 16:9 screens). In 2014, all episodes of the show that were originally produced and aired in standard definition before both the season 21 premiere and the show's initial conversion to HD capability simultaneously in 2010 and/or already airing in rerun syndication for almost over a decade or more (and still are) got stretched vertically downward with slightly re-edited graphics due to widescreen and HD broadcast capability and signals on more broadcast television stations (and cable) networks, ''AFV''{{'}}s 25th anniversary, Tom Bergeron's 15th and final year as host of the show, and Alfonso Ribiero's entrance as the current host in season 26 that also included an almost-brand-new set, new version of the theme song, new graphics, and new logo among other things; while the funny video clips recorded with the use of camcorders before 2009 or the years preceding the invention of today's mobile devices such as the iPhone or iPad (and especially the videos that were aired on episodes in the Bob Saget, John Fugelsang, Daisy Fuentes, and the early Tom Bergeron eras of ''AFV'') continued (and still continue in the Alfonso Ribiero run of ''AFV'') to be stretched horizontally to this day.\n\n==Series overview==\n{{Series overview\n| auxA       = Host(s)\n| infoA      = Rank\n| infoB      = Average viewers<br />(in millions)\n\n| color0S    = #\n| linkT0S    = Special\n| auxA0S     = [[Bob Saget]]\n| episodes0S = 1\n| start0S    = {{Start date|1989|11|26}}\n| infoA0S    = {{N/a}}\n| infoB0S    = 32.0<ref name=\"LATimesJul2017\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-abc-funniest-videos-20170718-story.html |title=Even in the age of YouTube, 'America's Funniest Home Videos' is still an ABC hit |last=Battaglio |first=Stephen |date=July 18, 2017 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416034607/https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-abc-funniest-videos-20170718-story.html |archive-date=April 16, 2020 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| color1     = #\n| episodes1  = 15\n| start1     = {{Start date|1990|1|14}}\n| end1       = {{End date|1990|5|20}}\n| infoA1     = 5\n| infoB1     = 20.9<ref name=\"1989-92TopShows\">{{Cite book |last1=Brooks |first1=Tim |author-link1=Tim Brooks (television historian) |last2=Marsh |first2=Earle |title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows 1946\u2013Present |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=w8KztFy6QYwC&pg=PA1692 |url-status=live |edition=9th |publisher=[[Ballantine Books]] |pages=1692\u20131693 |date=2007 |isbn=978-0-345-49773-4 |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n| color2     = #\n| episodes2  = 25\n| start2     = {{Start date|1990|9|16}}\n| end2       = {{End date|1991|5|12}}\n| infoA2     = 7\n| infoB2     = 16.7<ref name=\"1989-92TopShows\" />\n\n| color3     = #\n| episodes3  = 25\n| start3     = {{Start date|1991|9|22}}\n| end3       = {{End date|1992|5|17}}\n| infoA3     = 20\n| infoB3     = 14.5<ref name=\"1989-92TopShows\" /><ref name=\"1991-92AvgRatings\">{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/4678a051626ef6cb1d41c646dc259126 |title=The Season\u2019s Top-Rated Shows for 1991-92 With AM-Nielsen-Season Ratings |date=April 14, 1992 |work=[[Associated Press]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.is/H2tJ9 |archive-date=April 16, 2020 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| color4     = #\n| episodes4  = 25\n| start4     = {{Start date|1992|9|20}}\n| end4       = {{End date|1993|5|16}}\n| infoA4     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB4     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color5     = #\n| episodes5  = 22\n| start5     = {{Start date|1993|9|19}}\n| end5       = {{End date|1994|5|22}}\n| infoA5     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB5     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color6     = #\n| episodes6  = 23\n| start6     = {{Start date|1994|9|18}}\n| end6       = {{End date|1995|5|21}}\n| infoA6     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB6     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color7     = #\n| episodes7  = 22\n| start7     = {{Start date|1995|9|17}}\n| end7       = {{End date|1996|5|19}}\n| infoA7     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB7     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color8     = #\n| episodes8  = 30\n| start8     = {{Start date|1996|9|22}}\n| end8       = {{End date|1997|5|18}}\n| infoA8     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB8     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color9     = #\n| auxA9      = [[John Fugelsang]] and [[Daisy Fuentes]]\n| episodes9  = 23\n| start9     = {{Start date|1998|1|4}}\n| end9       = {{End date|1998|5|20}}\n| infoA9     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB9     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color10     = #\n| episodes10  = 23\n| start10     = {{Start date|1998|9|20}}\n| end10       = {{End date|1999|5|20}}\n| infoA10     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB10     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color11     = #\n| auxA11      = [[Tom Bergeron]]\n| episodes11  = 17\n| start11     = {{Start date|2001|7|3}}\n| end11       = {{End date|2002|1}}\n| infoA11     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB11     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color12     = #\n| episodes12  = 15\n| start12     = {{Start date|2002|1|4}}\n| end12       = {{End date|2002|5|17}}\n| infoA12     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB12     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color13     = #\n| episodes13  = 25\n| start13     = {{Start date|2002|9|27}}\n| end13       = {{End date|2003|5|9}}\n| infoA13     = {{N/a}}\n| infoB13     = {{N/a}}\n\n| color14     = #\n| episodes14  = 22\n| start14     = {{Start date|2003|9|28}}\n| end14       = {{End date|2004|5|23}}\n| infoA14     = 82\n| infoB14     = 8.02<ref name=\"2003-04AvgRatings\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/Web/progcal/dispDNR.aspx?id=060204_11 |title=I.T.R.S. Ranking Report: 9/22/03\u20135/30/04 |date=June 2, 2004 |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC Medianet]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521081534/http://www.abcmedianet.com/Web/progcal/dispDNR.aspx?id=060204_11 |archive-date=May 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n| color15     = #\n| episodes15  = 24\n| start15     = {{Start date|2004|9|26}}\n| end15       = {{End date|2005|5|13}}\n| infoA15     = 67\n| infoB15     = 8.40<ref name=\"2004-05AvgRatings\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=060105_05 |title=Season Program Rankings: 9/20/04\u20135/29/05 |date=June 1, 2005 |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC Medianet]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421023509/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=060105_05 |archive-date=April 21, 2012 |access-date=November 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\n| color16     = #\n| episodes16  = 26\n| start16     = {{Start date|2005|10|2}}\n| end16       = {{End date|2006|5|19}}\n| infoA16     = 64\n| infoB16     = 8.91<ref name=\"2005-06AvgRatings\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=053106_05 |title=Season Program Rankings: 9/19/05\u20135/28/06 |date=May 28, 2006 |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC Medianet]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011060406/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=053106_05 |archive-date=October 11, 2014 |access-date=May 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n| color17     = #\n| episodes17  = 25\n| start17     = {{Start date|2006|10|1}}\n| end17       = {{End date|2007|5|18}}\n| infoA17     = 73\n| infoB17     = 8.91<ref name=\"2006-07AvgRatings\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=053007_08 |title=Season Program Rankings: 9/18/06\u20135/27/07 |date=May 30, 2007 |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC Medianet]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323004317/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=053007_08 |archive-date=March 23, 2012 |access-date=May 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n| color18     = #\n| episodes18  = 23\n| start18     = {{Start date|2007|10|7}}\n| end18       = {{End date|2008|5|16}}\n| infoA18     = 86\n| infoB18     = 7.83<ref name=\"2007-08AvgRatings\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052808_06 |title=Seaso