V3 (Sweden)|TV3]]\n| 1991\u20131997\n| ''[[L\u00e5t L\u00e5t kameran g\u00e5]]''\n|-\n| {{GBR}}\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| 1990 \u2013 present\n| ''[[You've Been Framed!]]\n|-\n| {{AUS}}\n| [[Nine Network]]\n| 1990\u20132014\n| ''[[Australia's Funniest Home Videos]]''\n|-\n| {{FRA}}\n| [[TF1]]\n| 1990\u20132008\n| ''[[Video Gag]]''\n|-\n| {{NLD}}\n| [[TROS]]\n| 1990\u20132004\n| ''[[De De Leukste Thuis]]''\n|-\n| {{BEL}}\n| [[VTM (TV channel)|VTM]]\n| 1990\u20132004\n| ''[[Videodinges Videodinges]]''\n|-\n| {{NLD}}\n| [[SBS 6]]\n| 2002 \u2013 present\n| ''[[Lachen Lachen om Home Video's]]''\n|-\n|}-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0098740|title=America's Funniest Home Videos}}\n* {{tv.com show|americas-funniest-home-videos|America's Funniest Home Videos}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070603065822/http://www.shoutfactory.com/browse/5/americas_funniest_home_videos.aspx America's Funniest Home Videos] page from [[Shout! Factory]]\n* {{Official website|http://www.afv.com}}\n\n{{ABCNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n[[Category:1989 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980s American comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American video clip television series]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Japanese television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-TBS/WP:WCWproject (Spelling and typography - Missing end bold/italic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/America%27s_Funniest_Home_Videos"}
{"title_page": "The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{infobox music festival\n|music_festival_name = The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert for AIDS Awareness\n|image = Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert poster.jpg\n|caption = Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert poster\n|location = [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], [[London]], England\n|founders = [[Brian May]]<br />[[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]<br/>[[John Deacon]]\n|years_active= 1992\n|dates = 20 April 1992\n|genre = [[Benefit concert]]\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert for AIDS Awareness''' was a [[benefit concert]] held on [[Easter Monday]], 20 April 1992 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in [[London]], England for an audience of 72,000.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/24/newsid_2546000/2546945.stm 1991: Giant of rock dies] BBC News. Retrieved 25 May 2011</ref> The concert was produced for television by [[Ray Burdis]], directed by [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] and broadcast live on television and radio to 76 countries around the world, with an audience of up to one billion.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/abc2/200708/programs/ZY9027A001D20082007T210000.htm Freddie Mercury: The Tribute Concert] ABC Television (20 August 2007). Retrieved 29 August 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://queen.musichall.cz/en/discography/the-freddie-mercury-tribute-concert-vhs.html|title=Queen - Royal Legend: Discography: The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert VHS|first=|last=LG|website=queen.musichall.cz}}</ref> The concert was a tribute to [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s lead vocalist, [[Freddie Mercury]], who died of [[AIDS]] on 24 November 1991. The show marked bassist [[John Deacon]]'s final full-length concert with Queen (save a short live appearance with [[Brian May]], [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] and [[Elton John]] in 1997). The profits from the concert were used to launch [[The Mercury Phoenix Trust]], an AIDS charity organisation.\n\n== History ==\t\nFollowing [[Freddie Mercury]]'s death on 24 November 1991 from [[bronchopneumonia]] brought on by [[AIDS]], the remaining members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] ([[John Deacon]], [[Brian May]] and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]) came together with their manager [[Jim Beach]] to organize a concert to celebrate the life and legacy of Mercury, and to raise money for AIDS research and spread awareness about the disease.<ref name=\"Times\"/> In February 1992, at the annual [[BRIT Awards]] ceremony, May and Taylor announced plans for the concert. When tickets finally went on sale, all 72,000 tickets sold out in just three hours, even though no performers were announced apart from remaining members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]].<ref name=\"Times\">[http://www.queenarchives.com/index.php?title=Queen_-_04-21-1992_-_The_Times_-_Freddie_Mercury_Tribute Freddie Mercury Tribute] The Times. Retrieved 27 August 2011</ref>\n\n== Concert ==\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"Good evening Wembley and the world. We are here tonight to celebrate the life, and work, and dreams, of one Freddie Mercury. We're gonna give him the biggest send off in history!\"\n | source =&nbsp;\u2014Queen guitarist [[Brian Gay]].<ref name=\"intro\">[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/videos/fmtribute.htm#godsave Queen Introduction: The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert] Ultimate Queen. Retrieved 27 August 2011</ref>\n | width = 25%\n | align = right\n | style = padding:10px;\n}}\nThe concert opened with a message from the three remaining members of Queen in tribute to Mercury.<ref name=\"intro\"/> The music then commenced with short sets from artists that were influenced by the music of Queen, including [[Metallica]], [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] (playing a Queen medley), [[Def Leppard]] (who brought Brian May onstage for a version of \"[[Now I'm Here]]\"), and [[Guns N' Roses]]. Between bands, several video clips honouring Freddie Mercury were shown while [[Road crew|roadies]] changed the stage for the following act's performance. [[Elizabeth Taylor]] then gave an AIDS prevention speech, which was followed by a compilation of Mercury's various interactions with audiences.\n\nThe second half of the concert featured the three remaining Queen members \u2013 [[John Deacon]] (on bass), [[Brian May]] (on guitar) and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] (on drums) \u2013 along with guest singers and guitarists, including [[Elton John]], [[Roger Daltrey]] (of [[The Who]]), [[Tony Iommi]] (of [[Black Sabbath]]), [[David Bowie]], [[Mick Ronson]] (of [[Spiders from Mars]]), [[James Hetfield]] (of [[Metallica]]), [[George Michael]], [[Seal (musician)|Seal]], [[Paul Young (singer and guitarist)|Paul Young]], [[Annie Lennox]], [[Lisa Stansfield]], [[Robert Plant]] (of [[Led Zeppelin]]), [[Joe Elliott]] and [[Phil Collen]] (of [[Def Leppard]]), [[Axl Rose]] and [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] (of [[Guns N' Roses]]), [[Liza Minnelli]], and others. Via satellite from Sacramento, California, [[U2]] dedicated a live performance of \"[[Until the End of the World (song)|Until the End of the World]]\" to Mercury.<ref>[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/live/queen4.htm#1992freddietribute 1992 The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert] Ultimate Queen. Retrieved 29 August 2011</ref>\n\n== Home releases ==\nThe concert was originally released in VHS form (usually in two tape releases worldwide), but due to time limitations, \"Love of My Life\" and \"More Than Words\" by Extreme, \"Animal\" and \"Let's Get Rocked\" by Def Leppard, Spinal Tap's \"The Majesty of Rock\", U2's \"Until The End of the World\", [[Mango Groove]]'s \"[[Mango Groove (album)#Special Star|Special Star]]\" and Robert Plant's version of \"Innuendo\" were removed in the original release. The US release also omitted [[Bob Geldof]]'s performance of \"Too Late God\", and [[Zucchero Fornaciari]]'s performance of \"[[Las Palabras de Amor]]\".\n\nIn April 2002, for the 10th anniversary of the Mercury Phoenix Trust, the second half of the concert featuring the performances by the surviving members of Queen was released on DVD and entered the UK charts at number 1.<ref>[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/videos/fmtributedvd.htm The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert (Special 10th Anniversary Reissue)] Retrieved 25 May 2011</ref> \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" was not included on the DVD, at the request of [[Robert Plant]]. In addition, the original 4:3 footage had been cropped down to widescreen.\n\nOn 24 June 2013, Queen announced on their [[Facebook]] page that a new remastered version of the concert would be released in late 2013 on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Queen/posts/10151535807332362|title=Queen|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> The DVD and Blu-ray was released on 2 September 2013. Like the earlier, VHS release, this version excludes Extreme's \"Love of My Life\" and \"More Than Words\", Def Leppard's \"Animal\" and \"Let's Get Rocked\", Spinal Tap, U2 and Mango Groove from the opening acts segment of the show, and Robert Plant's \"Innuendo\" from the Queen+ segment of the show.\n\nClips of rehearsals and of Metallica's set (as well as James Hetfield's performance of Stone Cold Crazy with Queen and Tony Iommi) were featured in the 1992 documentary [[A Year and a Half in the Life of Metallica]].\n\nSeveral songs from the concert have also been released in audio-only format: \n*Metallica's 3-song performance was made into a UK tour edition single for \"Nothing Else Matters\", entitled \"Live at Wembley Stadium\" and released in Europe just one week after the concert, on 27 April 1992. \n*Guns N' Roses performance of \"Knockin' on Heaven's Door\" was released in August 1992 as a double A-side with the original Guns N' Roses studio recording of the song; it was also later featured on the band's ''[[Live Era '87\u2013'93]]'' album. The single entered the UK singles chart at No. 2. \n*Def Leppard released their version of \"Now I'm Here\" with Brian May from the concert as a B-side to their \"[[Tonight (Def Leppard song)|Tonight]]\" single.\n*An EP of the George Michael performances with Queen was released as ''[[Five Live (George Michael and Queen EP)|Five Live]]'' in April 1993. It entered the UK singles chart at No. 1. \n*Queen + David Bowie performances of the songs \"All the Young Dudes\" and \"Heroes\" were released on the soundtrack album to the film ''Beside Bowie: The Mick Ronson Story'' in 2018.\n\n==Performances==\n\n=== Without Queen ===\n#[[Metallica]] \u2013 \"[[Enter Sandman]]\", \"[[Sad but True]]\", \"[[Nothing Else Matters]]\"\n#[[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] \u2013 Queen Medley, \"[[Love of My Life (Queen song)|Love of My Life]]\", \"[[More Than Words]]\" (Gary Cherone & Nuno Bettencourt)\n#[[Def Leppard]] \u2013 \"[[Animal (Def Leppard song)|Animal]]\", \"[[Let's Get Rocked]]\", \"[[Now I'm Here]]\" (with [[Brian May]])\n#[[Bob Geldof]] \u2013 \"Too Late God\"\n#[[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]] \u2013 \"The Majesty of Rock\"\n#[[U2]] \u2013 \"[[Until the End of the World (song)|Until the End of the World]]\" \u2013 played via satellite from Sacramento, California\n#[[Guns N' Roses]] \u2013 \"[[Paradise City]]\", \"[[Only Women Bleed]]\", \"[[Knockin' on Heaven's Door]]\"\n#[[Mango Groove]] \u2013 \"[[Special Star (Mango Groove song)|Special Star]]\" \u2013 played via satellite from Johannesburg, South Africa\n#[[Elizabeth Taylor]] \u2013 AIDS Prevention Speech\n#[[Freddie Mercury]] \u2013 compilation of various interactions with the audience\n\n=== With Queen ===\n#[[Queen (band)|Queen]] + [[Joe Elliott]] & [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] \u2013 \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\"\n#Queen + [[Roger Daltrey]] & [[Tony Iommi]] \u2013 \"[[Heaven and Hell (Black Sabbath song)|Heaven and Hell]]\" (intro), \"[[Pinball Wizard]]\" (intro), \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\"\n#Queen + [[Zucchero]] \u2013 \"[[Las Palabras de Amor]]\"\n#Queen + [[Gary Cherone]] & Tony Iommi \u2013 \"[[Hammer to Fall]]\"\n#Queen + [[James Hetfield]] & Tony Iommi \u2013 \"[[Stone Cold Crazy]]\"\n#Queen + [[Robert Plant]] \u2013 \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" (including parts of \"[[Kashmir (song)|Kashmir]]\"), \"[[Thank You (Led Zeppelin song)|Thank You]]\" (intro), \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\"\n#[[Brian May]] + [[Spike Edney]] \u2013 \"[[Too Much Love Will Kill You]]\"\n#Queen + [[Paul Young (singer and guitarist)|Paul Young]] \u2013 \"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\"\n#Queen + [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\"\n#Queen + [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 \"[[I Want to Break Free]]\"\n#Queen + [[David Bowie]] & [[Annie Lennox]] \u2013 \"[[Under Pressure]]\"\n#Queen + [[Ian Hunter (singer)|Ian Hunter]], David Bowie, [[Mick Ronson]], Joe Elliott & [[Phil Collen]] \u2013 \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n#Queen + David Bowie & Mick Ronson \u2013 \"[[Heroes (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]\"\n#David Bowie \u2013 \"[[Lord's Prayer]]\"\n#Queen + [[George Michael]] \u2013 \"[['39]]\"\n#Queen + George Michael & Lisa Stansfield \u2013 \"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\"\n#Queen + George Michael \u2013 \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\"\n#Queen + [[Elton John]] & [[Axl Rose]] \u2013 \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\" Using the same light show as [[The Magic Tour]] from 1986 for the opera section and vocals played from a tape using the original 1970s\u2019 studio recording featuring [[Freddie Mercury]].\n#Queen + Elton John & Tony Iommi \u2013 \"[[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)|The Show Must Go On]]\"\n#Queen + Axl Rose \u2013 \"[[We Will Rock You]]\"\n#Queen + [[Liza Minnelli]] supported by everyone else who performed at the concert \u2013 \"[[We Are the Champions]]\"\n#Queen \u2013 \"[[God Save the Queen (Queen song)|God Save the Queen]]\" (taped outro)\n\n=== Queen's activity ===\n* [[Freddie Mercury]] \u2013 pre-recorded piano and vocals (on \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\") & compilation of various interactions with the audience during the section before the Queen + section of the concert.\n* [[Brian May]] \u2013 electric and acoustic guitars, keyboards (on \"[[Too Much Love Will Kill You]]\" and \"[[Who Wants To Live Forever]]\"), lead vocals on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\" (for verse 1, then co-lead vocals with [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] on 1st chorus on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\") and \"[[Too Much Love Will Kill You]]\", co-lead vocals (on \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\"), backing vocals\n* [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] \u2013 drums, tambourine, backing vocals, co-lead vocals on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\" (with [[Brian May]] on 1st chorus) and on [[Under Pressure]] (as a trio with [[David Bowie]] and [[Annie Lennox]] on choruses).\n* [[John Deacon]] \u2013 bass, additional backing vocals\n\n=== Guest musicians ===\n* [[Elton John]] \u2013 piano on \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\", lead vocals on \"Bohemian Rhapsody\" (verses only, then co-lead vocals with Axl Rose on final part)and \"The Show Must Go On\"\n* [[Axl Rose]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Bohemian Rhapsody\" (on final part, then co-lead vocals with Elton John) and \"We Will Rock You\"\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] \u2013 electric guitar on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\" (solo and final chords)\n* [[Tony Iommi]] \u2013 electric guitar on \"[[Heaven and Hell (Black Sabbath song)|Heaven and Hell]]\" (intro), \"[[Pinball Wizard]]\" (intro), \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\", \"[[Hammer to Fall]]\", \"[[Stone Cold Crazy]]\" & [[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)|The Show Must Go On]]\n* [[Roger Daltrey]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"I Want It All\"\n* [[Gary Cherone]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Hammer to Fall\n* [[James Hetfield]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Stone Cold Crazy\"\n* [[Ian Hunter (singer)|Ian Hunter]] \u2013 electric guitar and lead vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n* [[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 electric guitar on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\" and \"[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]\" \n* [[David Bowie]] - alto saxophone and backing vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\", lead vocals on \"Heroes\", co-lead vocals on \"Under Pressure\"\n* [[Annie Lennox]] \u2013 co-lead vocals on \"Under Pressure\"\n* [[Joe Elliott]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Tie Your Mother Down\" (except for verse 1 and 1st chorus, due to he enters to stage) backing vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n* [[Phil Collen]] \u2013 backing vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n* [[Zucchero]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"[[Las Palabras de Amor]]\"\n* [[Robert Plant]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" (including parts of \"[[Kashmir (song)|Kashmir]]\"), \"[[Thank You (Led Zeppelin song)|Thank You]]\" (intro) and \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\"\n* [[Paul Young (singer and guitarist)|Paul Young]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"[[Radio Ga-Ga]]\"\n* [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Who Wants to Live Forever\"\n* [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"I Want to Break Free\", co-lead vocals on \"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\"\n* [[George Michael]] \u2013 lead vocals \"[['39]]\" and \"Somebody to Love\", co-lead vocals on \"These Are the Days of Our Lives\"\n* [[Liza Minnelli]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"We Are the Champions\"\n* All guests (including [[Kirk Hammett]], [[Jason Newsted]], [[Lars Ulrich]], [[Nuno Bettencourt]], [[Pat Badger]], [[Paul Geary]], [[Vivian Campbell]], [[Rick Savage]], [[Rick Allen (drummer)|Rick Allen]], [[Bob Geldof]], [[Gilby Clarke]], [[Duff McKagan]], [[Matt Sorum]], [[Dizzy Reed]], [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and all members of [[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]]) \u2013 support on \"We Are the Champions\"\n\n=== Backing musicians ===\nQueen were backed by the following musicians:\n* [[Spike Edney]] \u2013 keyboards, piano, backing vocals\n* [[Mike Moran (music producer)|Mike Moran]] \u2013 piano on \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\" and \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\"\n* [[Josh Macrae]] \u2013 percussion in some Queen tracks\n* [[Chris Thompson (English musician)|Chris Thompson]] \u2013 backing vocals, acoustic guitar on \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\", \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\" and \"[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]\", additional percussion\n* [[Maggie Ryder]] \u2013 backing vocals\n* [[Miriam Stockley]] \u2013 backing vocals\n* [[London Community Gospel Choir]] \u2013 backing vocals on \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\" and \"[[We Are the Champions]]\"\n* John Jones \u2013 organ and backing vocals on \"[[We Are the Champions]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0103999|title=Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert}}\n*[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/Videos/fmtributedvd.htm Transcript of the DVD edition]\n\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Music|1990s}}\n\n{{Freddie Mercury}}\n{{Queen}}\n{{Liza Minnelli}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert, The}}\n[[Category:Queen (band) video albums]]\n[[Category:Benefit concerts in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Freddie Mercury]]\n[[Category:Tribute concerts in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Concerts at Wembley Stadium]]\n[[Category:1992 in London]]\n[[Category:1992 in music]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records video albums]]\n[[Category:April 1992 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{infobox music festival\n|music_festival_name = The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert for AIDS Awareness\n|image = Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert poster.jpg\n|caption = Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert poster\n|location = [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], [[London]], England\n|founders = [[Brian May]]<br />[[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]<br/>[[John Deacon]]\n|years_active= 1992\n|dates = 20 April 1992\n|genre = [[Benefit concert]]\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert for AIDS Awareness''' was a [[benefit concert]] held on [[Easter Monday]], 20 April 1992 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in [[London]], England for an audience of 72,000.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/24/newsid_2546000/2546945.stm 1991: Giant of rock dies] BBC News. Retrieved 25 May 2011</ref> The concert was produced for television by [[Ray Burdis]], directed by [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] and broadcast live on television and radio to 76 countries around the world, with an audience of up to one billion.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/abc2/200708/programs/ZY9027A001D20082007T210000.htm Freddie Mercury: The Tribute Concert] ABC Television (20 August 2007). Retrieved 29 August 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://queen.musichall.cz/en/discography/the-freddie-mercury-tribute-concert-vhs.html|title=Queen - Royal Legend: Discography: The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert VHS|first=|last=LG|website=queen.musichall.cz}}</ref> The concert was a tribute to [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s lead vocalist, [[Freddie Mercury]], who died of [[AIDS]] on 24 November 1991. The show marked bassist [[John Deacon]]'s final full-length concert with Queen (save a short live appearance with [[Brian May]], [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] and [[Elton John]] in 1997). The profits from the concert were used to launch [[The Mercury Phoenix Trust]], an AIDS charity organisation.\n\n== History ==\t\nFollowing [[Freddie Mercury]]'s death on 24 November 1991 from [[bronchopneumonia]] brought on by [[AIDS]], the remaining members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] ([[John Deacon]], [[Brian May]] and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]) came together with their manager [[Jim Beach]] to organize a concert to celebrate the life and legacy of Mercury, and to raise money for AIDS research and spread awareness about the disease.<ref name=\"Times\"/> In February 1992, at the annual [[BRIT Awards]] ceremony, May and Taylor announced plans for the concert. When tickets finally went on sale, all 72,000 tickets sold out in just three hours, even though no performers were announced apart from remaining members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]].<ref name=\"Times\">[http://www.queenarchives.com/index.php?title=Queen_-_04-21-1992_-_The_Times_-_Freddie_Mercury_Tribute Freddie Mercury Tribute] The Times. Retrieved 27 August 2011</ref>\n\n== Concert ==\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"Good evening Wembley and the world. We are here tonight to celebrate the life, and work, and dreams, of one Freddie Mercury. We're gonna give him the biggest send off in history!\"\n | source =&nbsp;\u2014Queen guitarist [[Brian May]].<ref name=\"intro\">[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/videos/fmtribute.htm#godsave Queen Introduction: The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert] Ultimate Queen. Retrieved 27 August 2011</ref>\n | width = 25%\n | align = right\n | style = padding:10px;\n}}\nThe concert opened with a message from the three remaining members of Queen in tribute to Mercury.<ref name=\"intro\"/> The music then commenced with short sets from artists that were influenced by the music of Queen, including [[Metallica]], [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] (playing a Queen medley), [[Def Leppard]] (who brought Brian May onstage for a version of \"[[Now I'm Here]]\"), and [[Guns N' Roses]]. Between bands, several video clips honouring Freddie Mercury were shown while [[Road crew|roadies]] changed the stage for the following act's performance. [[Elizabeth Taylor]] then gave an AIDS prevention speech, which was followed by a compilation of Mercury's various interactions with audiences.\n\nThe second half of the concert featured the three remaining Queen members \u2013 [[John Deacon]] (on bass), [[Brian May]] (on guitar) and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] (on drums) \u2013 along with guest singers and guitarists, including [[Elton John]], [[Roger Daltrey]] (of [[The Who]]), [[Tony Iommi]] (of [[Black Sabbath]]), [[David Bowie]], [[Mick Ronson]] (of [[Spiders from Mars]]), [[James Hetfield]] (of [[Metallica]]), [[George Michael]], [[Seal (musician)|Seal]], [[Paul Young (singer and guitarist)|Paul Young]], [[Annie Lennox]], [[Lisa Stansfield]], [[Robert Plant]] (of [[Led Zeppelin]]), [[Joe Elliott]] and [[Phil Collen]] (of [[Def Leppard]]), [[Axl Rose]] and [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] (of [[Guns N' Roses]]), [[Liza Minnelli]], and others. Via satellite from Sacramento, California, [[U2]] dedicated a live performance of \"[[Until the End of the World (song)|Until the End of the World]]\" to Mercury.<ref>[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/live/queen4.htm#1992freddietribute 1992 The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert] Ultimate Queen. Retrieved 29 August 2011</ref>\n\n== Home releases ==\nThe concert was originally released in VHS form (usually in two tape releases worldwide), but due to time limitations, \"Love of My Life\" and \"More Than Words\" by Extreme, \"Animal\" and \"Let's Get Rocked\" by Def Leppard, Spinal Tap's \"The Majesty of Rock\", U2's \"Until The End of the World\", [[Mango Groove]]'s \"[[Mango Groove (album)#Special Star|Special Star]]\" and Robert Plant's version of \"Innuendo\" were removed in the original release. The US release also omitted [[Bob Geldof]]'s performance of \"Too Late God\", and [[Zucchero Fornaciari]]'s performance of \"[[Las Palabras de Amor]]\".\n\nIn April 2002, for the 10th anniversary of the Mercury Phoenix Trust, the second half of the concert featuring the performances by the surviving members of Queen was released on DVD and entered the UK charts at number 1.<ref>[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/videos/fmtributedvd.htm The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert (Special 10th Anniversary Reissue)] Retrieved 25 May 2011</ref> \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" was not included on the DVD, at the request of [[Robert Plant]]. In addition, the original 4:3 footage had been cropped down to widescreen.\n\nOn 24 June 2013, Queen announced on their [[Facebook]] page that a new remastered version of the concert would be released in late 2013 on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Queen/posts/10151535807332362|title=Queen|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> The DVD and Blu-ray was released on 2 September 2013. Like the earlier, VHS release, this version excludes Extreme's \"Love of My Life\" and \"More Than Words\", Def Leppard's \"Animal\" and \"Let's Get Rocked\", Spinal Tap, U2 and Mango Groove from the opening acts segment of the show, and Robert Plant's \"Innuendo\" from the Queen+ segment of the show.\n\nClips of rehearsals and of Metallica's set (as well as James Hetfield's performance of Stone Cold Crazy with Queen and Tony Iommi) were featured in the 1992 documentary [[A Year and a Half in the Life of Metallica]].\n\nSeveral songs from the concert have also been released in audio-only format: \n*Metallica's 3-song performance was made into a UK tour edition single for \"Nothing Else Matters\", entitled \"Live at Wembley Stadium\" and released in Europe just one week after the concert, on 27 April 1992. \n*Guns N' Roses performance of \"Knockin' on Heaven's Door\" was released in August 1992 as a double A-side with the original Guns N' Roses studio recording of the song; it was also later featured on the band's ''[[Live Era '87\u2013'93]]'' album. The single entered the UK singles chart at No. 2. \n*Def Leppard released their version of \"Now I'm Here\" with Brian May from the concert as a B-side to their \"[[Tonight (Def Leppard song)|Tonight]]\" single.\n*An EP of the George Michael performances with Queen was released as ''[[Five Live (George Michael and Queen EP)|Five Live]]'' in April 1993. It entered the UK singles chart at No. 1. \n*Queen + David Bowie performances of the songs \"All the Young Dudes\" and \"Heroes\" were released on the soundtrack album to the film ''Beside Bowie: The Mick Ronson Story'' in 2018.\n\n==Performances==\n\n=== Without Queen ===\n#[[Metallica]] \u2013 \"[[Enter Sandman]]\", \"[[Sad but True]]\", \"[[Nothing Else Matters]]\"\n#[[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] \u2013 Queen Medley, \"[[Love of My Life (Queen song)|Love of My Life]]\", \"[[More Than Words]]\" (Gary Cherone & Nuno Bettencourt)\n#[[Def Leppard]] \u2013 \"[[Animal (Def Leppard song)|Animal]]\", \"[[Let's Get Rocked]]\", \"[[Now I'm Here]]\" (with [[Brian May]])\n#[[Bob Geldof]] \u2013 \"Too Late God\"\n#[[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]] \u2013 \"The Majesty of Rock\"\n#[[U2]] \u2013 \"[[Until the End of the World (song)|Until the End of the World]]\" \u2013 played via satellite from Sacramento, California\n#[[Guns N' Roses]] \u2013 \"[[Paradise City]]\", \"[[Only Women Bleed]]\", \"[[Knockin' on Heaven's Door]]\"\n#[[Mango Groove]] \u2013 \"[[Special Star (Mango Groove song)|Special Star]]\" \u2013 played via satellite from Johannesburg, South Africa\n#[[Elizabeth Taylor]] \u2013 AIDS Prevention Speech\n#[[Freddie Mercury]] \u2013 compilation of various interactions with the audience\n\n=== With Queen ===\n#[[Queen (band)|Queen]] + [[Joe Elliott]] & [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] \u2013 \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\"\n#Queen + [[Roger Daltrey]] & [[Tony Iommi]] \u2013 \"[[Heaven and Hell (Black Sabbath song)|Heaven and Hell]]\" (intro), \"[[Pinball Wizard]]\" (intro), \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\"\n#Queen + [[Zucchero]] \u2013 \"[[Las Palabras de Amor]]\"\n#Queen + [[Gary Cherone]] & Tony Iommi \u2013 \"[[Hammer to Fall]]\"\n#Queen + [[James Hetfield]] & Tony Iommi \u2013 \"[[Stone Cold Crazy]]\"\n#Queen + [[Robert Plant]] \u2013 \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" (including parts of \"[[Kashmir (song)|Kashmir]]\"), \"[[Thank You (Led Zeppelin song)|Thank You]]\" (intro), \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\"\n#[[Brian May]] + [[Spike Edney]] \u2013 \"[[Too Much Love Will Kill You]]\"\n#Queen + [[Paul Young (singer and guitarist)|Paul Young]] \u2013 \"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\"\n#Queen + [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\"\n#Queen + [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 \"[[I Want to Break Free]]\"\n#Queen + [[David Bowie]] & [[Annie Lennox]] \u2013 \"[[Under Pressure]]\"\n#Queen + [[Ian Hunter (singer)|Ian Hunter]], David Bowie, [[Mick Ronson]], Joe Elliott & [[Phil Collen]] \u2013 \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n#Queen + David Bowie & Mick Ronson \u2013 \"[[Heroes (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]\"\n#David Bowie \u2013 \"[[Lord's Prayer]]\"\n#Queen + [[George Michael]] \u2013 \"[['39]]\"\n#Queen + George Michael & Lisa Stansfield \u2013 \"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\"\n#Queen + George Michael \u2013 \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\"\n#Queen + [[Elton John]] & [[Axl Rose]] \u2013 \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\" Using the same light show as [[The Magic Tour]] from 1986 for the opera section and vocals played from a tape using the original 1970s\u2019 studio recording featuring [[Freddie Mercury]].\n#Queen + Elton John & Tony Iommi \u2013 \"[[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)|The Show Must Go On]]\"\n#Queen + Axl Rose \u2013 \"[[We Will Rock You]]\"\n#Queen + [[Liza Minnelli]] supported by everyone else who performed at the concert \u2013 \"[[We Are the Champions]]\"\n#Queen \u2013 \"[[God Save the Queen (Queen song)|God Save the Queen]]\" (taped outro)\n\n=== Queen's activity ===\n* [[Freddie Mercury]] \u2013 pre-recorded piano and vocals (on \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\") & compilation of various interactions with the audience during the section before the Queen + section of the concert.\n* [[Brian May]] \u2013 electric and acoustic guitars, keyboards (on \"[[Too Much Love Will Kill You]]\" and \"[[Who Wants To Live Forever]]\"), lead vocals on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\" (for verse 1, then co-lead vocals with [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] on 1st chorus on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\") and \"[[Too Much Love Will Kill You]]\", co-lead vocals (on \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\"), backing vocals\n* [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] \u2013 drums, tambourine, backing vocals, co-lead vocals on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\" (with [[Brian May]] on 1st chorus) and on [[Under Pressure]] (as a trio with [[David Bowie]] and [[Annie Lennox]] on choruses).\n* [[John Deacon]] \u2013 bass, additional backing vocals\n\n=== Guest musicians ===\n* [[Elton John]] \u2013 piano on \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\", lead vocals on \"Bohemian Rhapsody\" (verses only, then co-lead vocals with Axl Rose on final part)and \"The Show Must Go On\"\n* [[Axl Rose]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Bohemian Rhapsody\" (on final part, then co-lead vocals with Elton John) and \"We Will Rock You\"\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] \u2013 electric guitar on \"[[Tie Your Mother Down]]\" (solo and final chords)\n* [[Tony Iommi]] \u2013 electric guitar on \"[[Heaven and Hell (Black Sabbath song)|Heaven and Hell]]\" (intro), \"[[Pinball Wizard]]\" (intro), \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\", \"[[Hammer to Fall]]\", \"[[Stone Cold Crazy]]\" & [[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)|The Show Must Go On]]\n* [[Roger Daltrey]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"I Want It All\"\n* [[Gary Cherone]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Hammer to Fall\n* [[James Hetfield]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Stone Cold Crazy\"\n* [[Ian Hunter (singer)|Ian Hunter]] \u2013 electric guitar and lead vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n* [[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 electric guitar on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\" and \"[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]\" \n* [[David Bowie]] - alto saxophone and backing vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\", lead vocals on \"Heroes\", co-lead vocals on \"Under Pressure\"\n* [[Annie Lennox]] \u2013 co-lead vocals on \"Under Pressure\"\n* [[Joe Elliott]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Tie Your Mother Down\" (except for verse 1 and 1st chorus, due to he enters to stage) backing vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n* [[Phil Collen]] \u2013 backing vocals on \"[[All the Young Dudes]]\"\n* [[Zucchero]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"[[Las Palabras de Amor]]\"\n* [[Robert Plant]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" (including parts of \"[[Kashmir (song)|Kashmir]]\"), \"[[Thank You (Led Zeppelin song)|Thank You]]\" (intro) and \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\"\n* [[Paul Young (singer and guitarist)|Paul Young]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"[[Radio Ga-Ga]]\"\n* [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"Who Wants to Live Forever\"\n* [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"I Want to Break Free\", co-lead vocals on \"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\"\n* [[George Michael]] \u2013 lead vocals \"[['39]]\" and \"Somebody to Love\", co-lead vocals on \"These Are the Days of Our Lives\"\n* [[Liza Minnelli]] \u2013 lead vocals on \"We Are the Champions\"\n* All guests (including [[Kirk Hammett]], [[Jason Newsted]], [[Lars Ulrich]], [[Nuno Bettencourt]], [[Pat Badger]], [[Paul Geary]], [[Vivian Campbell]], [[Rick Savage]], [[Rick Allen (drummer)|Rick Allen]], [[Bob Geldof]], [[Gilby Clarke]], [[Duff McKagan]], [[Matt Sorum]], [[Dizzy Reed]], [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and all members of [[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]]) \u2013 support on \"We Are the Champions\"\n\n=== Backing musicians ===\nQueen were backed by the following musicians:\n* [[Spike Edney]] \u2013 keyboards, piano, backing vocals\n* [[Mike Moran (music producer)|Mike Moran]] \u2013 piano on \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\" and \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\"\n* [[Josh Macrae]] \u2013 percussion in some Queen tracks\n* [[Chris Thompson (English musician)|Chris Thompson]] \u2013 backing vocals, acoustic guitar on \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\", \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\" and \"[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]\", additional percussion\n* [[Maggie Ryder]] \u2013 backing vocals\n* [[Miriam Stockley]] \u2013 backing vocals\n* [[London Community Gospel Choir]] \u2013 backing vocals on \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\" and \"[[We Are the Champions]]\"\n* John Jones \u2013 organ and backing vocals on \"[[We Are the Champions]]\"\n\